<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ariane 1stLd-Writethru a0619 12-11 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ariane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Rocket Lifts Off After 24-hour Delay</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD attribution, BACKGROUND on satellite,
Ariane, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Ariane 4 rocket lifted
off on its first commercial mission Saturday night after a 24-hour
delay and placed two satellites in orbit.
   The rocket blasted off at 9:34 p.m. (7:34 p.m. EST) from the
Kourou space center on the Atlantic coast of French Guiana, on the
northern coast of South America.
   About 30 minutes later, it deployed a satellite to broadcast TV
directly into European homes and another to be used for British
military communications, according to Arianespace President Frederic
D'Allest.
   In a last-minute hitch before liftoff, an instrument indicated a
malfunction of a valve on the third stage of the rocket. The
countdown stopped with 26 seconds left.
   But technicians checked the valve and found it in working order.
The countdown resumed after a 30-minute delay, and the launch went
on with no apparent problems.
   The countdown was halted Friday night minutes before liftoff when
a menacing storm cloud passed. It was later postponed because of a
faulty sensor on the rocket's third stage.
   The Ariane 4 model of the rocket took off just once before in a
demonstration launch last June, when it placed three satellites in
orbit. Saturday's launch represents the first commercial mission for
the latest, more powerful and versatile version of the Ariane
rockets.
   Arianespace is a private French-based consortium entrusted with
commercial launches of the Ariane rockets developed by the
13-national European Space Agency. The manufacture and assembly of
rocket components are divided among dozens of European companies to
give each country benefits proportional to its investment in
research and development.
   The European program has benefited from the troubles of the U.S.
space shuttle related to the explosion of the Challenger in 1986.
The Ariane program now has 40 satellites on its order book for
future launches.
   The Astra 1A satellite, owned by a Luxembourg-based consortium,
is designed to broadcast 16 channels of television programs that can
be received by home dishes as small as two-feet wide.
   Eleven of the channels are already sold, and plans are to begin
broadcasts in late January, offering all-news, all-sports,
all-movies and other programming available to 85 percent of West
European homes.
   Astra officials say they could eventually serve 55 million homes
directly and 25 million more via master antenna systems.
   Australian publisher and station owner Rupert Murdoch's News
International Group is the chief client.
   Another Ariane rocket last month launched a French competitor,
TDF-1, but it has not yet lined up programming for its six channels.
   The other satellite carried by Ariane 4, Britain's Skynet 4B,
represents the first of four such satellites which together will
provide a communications network for British navy submarines,
surface ships and ground stations.
</TEXT>
