<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DanceBan 2ndLd-Writethru a0637 12-11 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dance Ban, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0637,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Purdy High School Holds First Dance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with dance under way, quotes
from participants, other detail. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `U.S.
District...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XMON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURDY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Footloose students at Purdy High School broke a
100-year-old tradition Saturday night when they held the first dance
in the school's history in a gymnasium decorated with stars and
streamers.
   The students began filing into the gymnasium about 10:15 p.m. for
the dance after the Purdy basketball team lost to Billings High
School, 61-56. Most of the students were casually dressed, wearing
jeans and sweaters. But they seemed excited about being the first
students to dance in the school's gymnasium.
   ``I expect to have a really good time,'' said sophomore Ryan
Deayre, who moved to Purdy five years ago. ``I thought it was going
to be a dull town. Really, it's not a dull town anymore. I just wish
last year's seniors had had a chance to go to this dance.''
   The dance was limited to the 161 students in grades nine through
12 because school officials did not want anyone to disrupt it.
Journalists were allowed into the decorated gymnasium before the
dance.
   The school's ban on dancing, which brought national attention in
the wake of the hit movie ``Footloose'' about a similar ban in a
fictional town, was ruled unconstitutional this summer by a federal
judge.
   ``It's great,'' said senior Rhonda Robberson, who was crowned
homecoming queen Saturday night. ``It's a wonderful feeling. It's
going to be something I'll always remember.''
   The gymnasium at Purdy High School was transformed into a tent
from the Arabian Nights with stars hanging overhead.
   Students worked throughout the day stringing blue and white
streamers and hanging the stars, which recalled the theme of the
evening ``Waiting for a Star to Fall,'' a popular ballad by the rock
group Boy Meets Girl. Star-covered balloons were scattered over the
gymnasium floor.
   The lead plaintiff in the suit, Jonathan Clayton, could not
attend the dance because he is now attending business school in
Kansas City.
   He said he was disappointed, but ``it's still worth it. The idea
was to allow Purdy students to have a dance and we did that.''
   Superintendent Sheldon Buxton said alumni and other non-students
were kept out of the dance because he feared outsiders bent on
disruption would be attracted by publicity.
   ``This is our homecoming,'' he said. ``The kids are excited about
the dance.''
   U.S. District Judge Russell Clark ruled that the ban promoted the
values of those who oppose dancing for religious reasons. The board
appealed, but a federal appeals court allowed the dance to go on
while it considers the issue.
   Although barred from dancing at school, Purdy students have held
dances at the community center or in neighboring towns. But they
said that was inconvenient and unfair.
   ``I already live way outside of Purdy,'' said junior Anna
Svetlecic. ``My freshman year, I couldn't go to the homecoming dance
because it was too far. If we have them at school, everybody can
go.''
   Miss Svetlecic decided to go to the dance even though her
boyfriend, no longer a student, was not allowed to attend. She said
she didn't want to miss history in the making.
   Miss Svetlecic said she had been to only two dances _ one held at
the community center her freshman year, another staged in Kansas
City as a benefit for the lawsuit that challenged the dance ban.
   ``A lot of people have never even been to a dance,'' she said.
``They know how to dance, they just never got a chance.''
   Purdy residents say feelings ran high over the dance issue in the
farming community of about 900, in the Ozarks of southern Missouri.
   Supporters of the ban were known to cross the street to avoid
meeting someone in favor of the dance. About 250 people turned out
at a school board meeting in 1986, most favoring the dance ban.
   Students circulated petitions and held rallies in support of
dancing. They invited the stars of ``Footloose,'' a movie about a
fictional town with a dance ban, to a rally in 1986, but actors
Kevin Bacon and Christopher Penn did not attend.
   Three teachers volunteered as chaperones for the dance.
   School officials ``wouldn't even have the parents as
chaperones,'' said Walter Welch, whose daughter, Sherry, is a
student at Purdy High. ``We would have helped, we always do. But I
guess they wanted to do it themselves this time.''
</TEXT>
