<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Egypt-Violence     12-11 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Violence,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Wounded, Policeman Killed in Extremist Strife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival groups of Moslem fundamentalist
students battled with knives, chains, and sticks, and about 100 were
wounded, authorities said Saturday. A police officer was fatally
stabbed in Cairo, police sources said.
   Police and sources at Assiut University, where the clashes broke
out, said none of the students was seriously injured in the fighting
Wednesday and Thursday. However, tension remained high between
students of a militant faction known as Gamaat Islamiya and campus
members of the moderate Moslem Brotherhood.
   In Cairo, police sources said a nationwide search was under way
for a Moslem extremist suspected of fatally stabbing a senior police
officer in the working-class district of Ein Shams on Thursday.
   Security forces have rounded up more than 130 religious
extremists in Ein Shams since Wednesday, the sources said.
   Sixty-one were detained in a police sweep of fundamentalists'
homes in the Ein Shams area at dawn Wednesday as police followed up
a tip about an alleged sabotage conspiracy. Police found two
incendiary bombs, many knives and chains, and anti-government
leaflets.
   The Cairo police sources said 72 other extremists were rounded up
Thursday and Friday, 50 of them just outside an Ein Shams police
station they attacked with stones and flaming objects.
   But the state-owned newspaper Al-Ahram put the total number of
arrested at 186. It said they were charged with resisting
authorities, possessing and using explosives and knives, and
damaging public and private property.
   The clashes between student groups started at the university in
Assiut, about 240 miles south of Cairo. The campus has been a center
of Moslem extremist activity for years.
   Followers of the two groups have been feuding for months over
religious differences, such as which side should be allowed to
deliver sermons in the mosques.
   Both moderates and extremists support implementation of Sharia,
the Islamic legal and ethical code that was introduced about 14
centuries ago in the Moslem holy book, the Koran.
   Extremists advocate using violence, if necessary, in support of
the Moslem laws, while the Brotherhood says it is in favor of
peaceful action. The government contends more than 90 percent of
Egyptian laws already conform to the laws of Islam.
</TEXT>
