<1ST_LINE>u i BC-SovietQuake-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0649 12-11 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet Quake-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0649,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crashes While Approaching Airport in Disaster Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS message of condolence, background on weather, plane.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet military transport plane carrying soldiers
to help rescue victims of the Armenian earthquake crashed Sunday,
killing 79 people aboard, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said the crash occurred as the
Ilyushin-76 plane was approaching the airport in Leninakan, the
northern Armenian city near the epicenter of Wednesday's earthquake
that officials say killed at least 40,000 people.
   Nine crewmembers and 70 soldiers were killed in the crash, Tass
reported in a brief dispatch in the form of a message of condolences
from the Communist Party Central Committee and government. It did
not say how many people in all were aboard the heavy wide-body plane
and provided no further details.
   ``With a feeling of grief and compassion we express profound
condolences to the relatives and dear ones of the killed, who
hurried to help the fraternal Armenian people and earned the eternal
gratitude of the Soviet people,'' the message said.
   A massive international relief effort is under way to aid victims
from the temblor that measured 6.9 on the Richter scale. Officials
say at least 12,000 were hurt and a half-million are homeless.
   No weather problems were likely to have contributed to the crash,
the Soviet Meteorological Center told The Associated Press.
   Jane's All the World's Aircraft, a British reference book, says
the Ilyushin-76 is designed to land on short airstrips under
difficult weather conditions. It says the plane, which went into
service in 1971, has four-turbofan engines and can carry 40 tons of
freight.
</TEXT>
