<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiberaceAuction     12-11 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Auction,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace's Las Vegas Mansion Auctioned To Fans For $325,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The showplace mansion of the late Liberace, once
on the market for $2.8 million, sold at auction for $325,000 to fans
who said they wanted to preserve the memory of the flamboyant
entertainer.
   The estate about two miles from the Las Vegas Strip, where
Liberace was a headline performer for years, continues to draw
dozens of tour buses and taxicabs daily full of tourists seeking a
glimpse of the glittery pianist's home, said auctioneer Eric Nelson.
   James Harvey Sedger of Las Vegas, a retired oilman, and Lorna
Burroughs, a housewife from Phoenix, Ariz., pooled funds to make the
winning bid Saturday night.
   ``We plan to open it as a museum in his memory,'' Mrs. Burroughs
said after signing a deposit check and contract to buy the property.
``We want to keep it open to the public and preserve it as a
remembrance of his showmanship.''
   Sedger, 52, tossed his cowboy hat skyward in celebration when a
crowd of more than 100 well-dressed bidders failed to top his
successful bid.
   ``We're just trying to preserve a little bit of history,'' Sedger
said.
   The palatial, 10,549-square-foot home was originally listed at
$2.8 million after Liberace's death from AIDS complications in
February 1987.
   The home features a giant master bedroom with a painting of the
Sistine Chapel frescoes on the ceiling. The painting, by an Italian
artist, took nearly two years to complete.
   Between two bedrooms, at the end of a marble, mirrored hallway
called the eternal mirrors hallway, is a fountain and a sunken
bathtub, with a painting of Liberace on the ceiling.
   The patio area includes a pool, sauna, courtyard and dancing
fountains, a smaller version of the dancing waters attraction
Liberace used in his stage act.
   The home was stripped of furnishings earlier this year for
auctions in Southern California. Proceeds from the sale will go to
the Liberace Foundation for the Performing and Creative Arts, which
funds scholarships at 26 colleges and universities nationwide.
</TEXT>
