<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristmasTreats     12-11 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Treats,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Ends Up With Doggy Treats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to provide Christmas gifts for
Indian children has saddled the governor's Office of Indian Affairs
with a mountain of unwanted doggy treats.
   A 48-foot semi-truck load of donated Christmas gifts arrived from
New Jersey last month, containing several dozen stuffed animals and
other toys. But it mostly contained boxes of rawhide bones and chew
toys.
   ``After we cried and dried our eyes, we all had a good laugh,''
said Jennifer Scott, assistant director for the Office of Indian
Affairs.
   Ms. Scott had arranged for toys with Rick Rowe, an inmate at East
Jersey State Prison in Rahway, N.J., who for the past 11 years has
been able to persuade toy companies to donate gifts to American
Indian children and others. Spokane already has received two
truckloads.
   When the truck arrived at the Old Community Center in Olympia,
officials threw open the doors. There, stacked floor to ceiling,
were 12 dozen fluffy, stuffed animals, as well as key chains, mugs,
balloons and mixed candy.
   But behind the stuffed animals were 586 cases of doggy treats _
12 dozen treats to a case.
   ``Two-thirds of it was doggy treats,'' Ms. Scott said.
   Ms. Scott's staff distributed all of the toys and many of the
doggy treats to the tribes. But cases of doggy treats in plastic
Christmas stockings remained.
   Ms. Scott hopes Rowe can find one more truckload of toys before
Christmas.
   ``We're on the top of his list, but it's getting late,'' she said.
</TEXT>
