<1ST_LINE>r i AM-QuakeInsurance     12-11 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake Insurance,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Insurance Demand Skyrocketing In Western Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeowners who apparently were
alarmed by recent earthquakes in the Soviet Union and eastern Canada
are clamoring for quake insurance, industry officials say.
   Seismologists say the area has the potential for a damaging quake.
   ``Sixty percent of our customers are now asking for it,'' said
Barry Forbes, regional vice president of Wellington Insurance Co.
   Forbes said many callers in western Canada cited the temblor that
devastated Soviet Armenia last week and an earlier one that did less
damage in Quebec.
   ``Insurance brokers expect this interest will dry up as the
impact of the recent quake in the Soviet Union dies down,'' he said.
   Even before the recent quakes, however, concern about a temblor
strong enough to damage homes had been growing for about three
years, said Brian Stanhope, regional vice president of the Insurance
Bureau of Canada.
   Earthquake insurance costs less than $100 Canadian for a home
valued at $100,000, said Jack Adams of Adams Greer Insurance.
   Seismologist Garry Rogers of the Pacific Geoscience Center at
Sidney on Vancouver Island said a quake serious enough to cause
significant damage, about 6 on the Richter scale, could hit Canada's
West Coast at any time.
   In fact, insurance companies view earthquake damage as the
greatest disaster potential for that part of Canada and fear the
claims they could face if one occurred, Stanhope said.
   He said he took out quake insurance on his own home last month.
   ``Sooner or later we are going to have an earthquake,'' Stanhope
said. ``There's no doubt about that.''
</TEXT>
