<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Pope-Saint,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Canonizes Spanish Nun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday elevated to
sainthood a 19th century Spanish nun who founded a religious order
dedicated to helping the needy.
   The pope canonized Maria Rosa Molas Y Vallve in a solemn ceremony
in St. Peter's Basilica attended by 10,000 people, including 4,000
pilgrims from Spain.
   The nun, who lived from 1815 to 1876, was beatified by Pope Paul
VI in 1977.
   She founded the Congregation of Sisters of Our Lady of
Consolation to assist the sick and elderly, abandoned children and
other disadvanted people.
   In his homily, the pope said of the nun that ``although she lived
in difficult times, she gave proof of her profound faith, like so
many other saints and noble souls of Spain who were promoters of a
significant ecclesiastical renewal.''
