<HEAD>Pope Accepts Invitation To Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has accepted an
invitation from the president to visit Hungary, news reports said.
   The invitation was extended to the pontiff in August by President
Bruno F. Straub at the request of the Hungarian Catholic Episcopacy.
   No dates for the visit have been set, but Catholic sources in
Budapest said it may not occur until in 1990. It would be the pope's
first visit to an East European country other than his native Poland.
   In a report over the weekend, the official MTI news agency quoted
the pope's letter to Straub as saying:
   ``I'm happy to inform you that I have accepted the invitation in
the hope that my visit can give further encouragement to relations
between the noble Hungarian nation and the Apostolic Holy See, and
it will also be an occasion to strengthen the Sons of the Catholic
Church in their belief.''
