<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JailInmates     12-11 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Inmates,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embargoed for Release at 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Reports Increase in Local Jail Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's local jail population rose 32
percent in four years, the government reported Sunday, as police
made more arrests and facilities housed increasing numbers of
inmates from overcrowded state and federal prisons.
   The population of city, township and county jails was 296,873 on
June 30, 1987, compared to 223,551 for the same day four years
earlier, said the Bureau of Justice Statistics. The mid-1987 level
was up 8 percent from the previous year, when it was 274,444.
   Jails nationwide operated at 98 percent of their capacities in
1987 compared to 85 percent of capacity in 1983, according to the
annual survey.
   The increases in jail population were fed by larger numbers of
arrests during the four-year period and by the transfer of federal
and state prisoners into jail systems, said Susan Kline of the
bureau's staff, who compiled a report based on the jail data.
   Arrests of men rose 8 percent from 1983 to 1987 while arrests of
women rose 17 percent in that time, according to information
compiled by the FBI from police departments around the country.
Correspondingly, the number of women in jails rose 53 percent in the
four-year period, to 23,920 while the number of men rose 31 percent
to 295,873.
   The number of federal and state prisoners being held in local
jails was 26,800 in mid-1987, up by more than 3,600 in 12 months. As
of mid-1987, about 87 percent of large jail systems with at least
100 inmates were holding inmates for federal or state authorities.
   The government surveyed jails administered by city, township or
county officials holding inmates usually for more than 48 hours
following their arraignment.
   The study excluded temporary lockups, federal and state prisons,
private correctional facilities and the combined jail-and-prison
systems in half-a-dozen states.
</TEXT>
