<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44, TOK16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wynonna Judd says she is no longer a
``jerk'' now that she and her mother, Naomi, are a successful
country vocal duo.
   The two recently marked the release of ``The Judds' Greatest
Hits,'' which was certified gold five years after the pair entered
the Nashville music scene with No. 1 ``Mama He's Crazy.''
   ``Success has helped me to feel confident,'' Wynonna Judd said.
``A lot of it is just feeling that Wynonna Judd's an OK person.
She's not a jerk anymore.
   ``I was very insecure: my weight, insecure about boys, just
everything that kids go through. Now for the first time in my life I
feel like I have one thing that no one can take away from me.
   ``I can look at these walls at RCA and see our platinum albums
and know that my one true great gift is music,'' the 24-year-old
singer said in a recent interview at RCA's Music Row office.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne, president of the Save The Children
charity and only daughter of Queen Elizabeth II, says she doesn't
much like children.
   In an interview being screened Sunday on London Weekend
Television, a commercial station, Anne, 38, said that when she
became interested in the fund in the 1970s, ``I wasn't particularly
keen on children _ and I'm still not.''
   ``But you don't actually have to like children very much to be
interested in giving them the best possible start in life,'' said
Anne, who has two children. ``And that is quite important for a lot
of people to remember.''
   A transcript of the 55-minute interview, the longest TV interview
ever given by a member of the British royal family, was released
Saturday.
   Anne and her husband, Capt. Mark Phillips, have an 11-year-old
son, Peter, and 7-year-old daughter, Zara.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, Michael Jackson, Eddie
Murphy, Whoopi Goldberg and Clint Eastwood were among those honored
at the 21st annual NAACP Image Awards.
   ``Coming To America'' was named best movie and NBC's ``The Cosby
Show'' best TV comedy at a National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People ceremony honoring black achievement.
   Saturday night's show will be broadcast Jan. 14 on NBC.
   Jesse Jackson received an award for public service. Eastwood, who
directed ``Bird,'' which chronicled the life of jazz musician
Charlie Parker, received a special award for using blacks in his
films in positive, non-stereotypical roles, said NAACP spokeswoman
Dawna Culpepper.
   Eastwood thanked the NAACP and said he looked forward to the day
when such racial awards would be ``obsolete.''
   Murphy, who starred in ``Coming To America,'' was named black
entertainer of the year. Michael Jackson was honored as best male
recording artist and for best album, ``Bad.'' He also shared a
humanitarian award with singer Lou Rawls.
   Miss Goldberg was named best film actress for her work in ``Fatal
Beauty.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Otis
Bowen says he's looking forward to retiring to his tiny hometown of
Bremen, and he's leaving 36 years of public service with no regrets.
   ``I think it helped me understand problems a little bit better,''
Bowen said. ``I have no quarrel with anyone who wants to go into
public service. Politics is only as dirty as people let it become.''
   Bowen began his political career as county coroner, served two
terms as governor in the 1970s, then in December 1985 became the
first physician ever to head the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services.
   His term at the agency, which has almost 120,000 employees, ends
Jan. 20.
   ``I am looking forward to retiring to my five-acre plot in Bremen
and do the usual things that a retired person should do,'' Bowen
said in an interview published Sunday in The Indianapolis Star.
   ``That's read a little more, write some, travel and be of
whatever use I can to my community and state. That doesn't mean
running for office or accepting any full-time position in anything.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine-year-old Ayana Takada, who says she's been
listening to the music of Michael Jackson as long as she can
remember, was selected Sunday as the 4 millionth person to attend a
concert of Jackson's world tour.
   Jackson, who opened the last leg of his world tour in Tokyo
Friday night, brought the girl on stage during his performance
Sunday and presented her with a certificate commemorating the event.
   By the time he winds up his 12-nation tour, the rock star is
expected to have performed before a record 4.4 million fans,
according to tour organizers.
   Jackson, 30, embarked on his first international solo tour in
Japan in September 1987, playing before sold-out crowds in 14
concerts.
   Jackson wants to retire from the tour circuit after winding up
his show in Japan on Dec. 26, said his manager, Frank Dileo.
   ``This is probably the last time Michael will be on tour,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
