<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan-Crash     12-11 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Crash,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Kabul Says Pakistan Downed Commercial Jet, Killing 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's official radio reported
Sunday that a Pakistani warplane shot down a commercial jet flying
inside Afghanistan and that all 25 people aboard died.
   Radio Kabul said the Pakistan fighter plane downed the
Soviet-made Antonov-26 commercial airliner about 8 p.m. Saturday as
it was flying from the eastern district of Khost to Kabul, the
Afghan capital.
   The radio broadcast, which was monitored in Islamabad, said three
children and a woman were among the dead. The report contained no
other details.
   Pakistan government officials could not be reached for comment.
   Spokesman at the Foreign Ministry have repeatedly denied charges
by the Soviet-backed Afghan government that Pakistan fighters enter
Afghan airspace.
   Afghanistan and Pakistan, which signed a U.N. accord in April
providing for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet troops from
Afghanistan, have often charged each other with mounting air and
missile attacks.
   U.S.-backed Afghan guerrillas headquartered in Pakistan have been
fighting the communist government in Kabul for the past 10 years.
   On Nov. 21, Radio Kabul accused Pakistan of shooting down a
commercial plane that had strayed into Pakistani airspace and
killing all 27 on board. The report said the aircraft strayed off
course after developing technical problems. It was shot down several
miles inside Pakistan territory.
   Pakistan acknowledged downing a plane, but identified it as a
military transport aircraft.
   A Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said in an earlier interview that Pakistan's air force has standing
orders to shoot down intruding Afghan military planes providing the
pilot is confident the downed plane will land in Pakistan territory
to prove the intrusion.
</TEXT>
