<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     12-11 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistani Legislators To Elect President on Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistani lawmakers will choose among
four presidential candidates Monday but the incumbent, Ghulam Ishaq
Khan, is the strong favorite to win a new five-year term.
   About 800 members of the Senate, the National Assembly and the
four provincial assemblies will act as an electoral college.
   Of the four candidates, only Ishaq Khan of the conservative
Pakistan Muslim League, has the support of Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party and the right-wing opposition
alliance, headed by the Muslim League.
   The other candidates are Nawabzada Nasrullah Khan of the tiny
right-of-center Pakistan Democratic Party; Ahmed E.H. Jaffar, an
industrialist from Karachi who is an independent; and Mohammad
Nauroz Malik, a member of the National Assembly also running as an
independent.
   Ms. Bhutto said Sunday in a statement issued through Pakistan's
official news agency that she would hold a vote of confidence four
hours after the presdidential balloting Monday.
   Under Pakistan's Constitution a government leader must call a
vote of confidence within 60 days of taking power. On Dec. 1, Ms.
Bhutto became the first woman to head a Moslem country in modern
times.
   Ishaq Khan, 73, has been credited with guiding Pakistan back to
democracy after 11 years of autocratic rule under President Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq, eight of them through martial law.
   Zia and U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel were killed Aug. 17 in
an explosion that destroyed their aircraft. Investigators blamed the
crash on sabotage but could not say exactly how it was done or by
whom.
   After Zia's death, the presidency automatically passed to Senate
Chairman Ishaq Khan, a constitutional scholar with nearly 40 years
in senior administrative posts, six of them as Minister of Finance
and Commerce.
   As president, Ishaq Khan proceeded with November general
elections that were scheduled by Zia.
   A constitutional amendment Zia pushed through parliament in 1985
gave the president broad but vaguely-defined powers.
   Ms. Bhutto has called for a repeal of that amendment, which would
restore supreme political powers to the prime minister.
   A repeal would require a two-thirds majority in the Senate and
the National Assembly, but Ms. Bhutto's party has not yet introduced
the legislation.
</TEXT>
