<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CasualGovernment     12-11 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Casual Government,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Residents Surprised To Find They Have A Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOOLSEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents of Woolsey, population 186
more or less, have just discovered they have a mayor and a city
council, and they don't like them one bit.
   Suddenly civic-minded residents have also learned that election
notices are posted on an old Coke machine in a car repair garage.
There's a city charter, too _ tucked in a drawer in a city
councilman's home.
   The charter provides for elections every September but there
haven't been any in some time because no one has run against the
incumbents. Albert Berg Sr. says he lost the mayor's job 12 years
ago to Lawrence Zeller, but Zeller said he thinks he has been mayor
now for only five or six years.
   The government meets at the fire station to discuss city business
``when something comes up,'' according to Zeller.
   ``We got a peaceful little town here,'' Councilman James Carden
said. ``We're not trying to hide anything. The people that are
complaining have been here five months, a year, if that long,'' he
told the Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution.
   People from nearby Atlanta have been moving into the area,
bringing along citified ideas of how government should operate.
   But the newcomers aren't the only ones looking surprised. Says
Cynthia Carpenter, who has lived on the town's main street for seven
years: ``Until a few months ago, we didn't know who the mayor was,
which was probably negligence on our part.''
   The town government started becoming an issue when construction
began on a convenience store on the town's main street.
   Neighbors were outraged. They got madder when they discovered
Carden had sold the land _ apparently zoned residential _ to a
developer and then, they claim, he voted with the rest of the
government to rezone the land commercial.
   Some people want an injunction to halt construction, and a recall
move is afoot.
   ``I want it stopped,'' said Earline Lockhart, who moved to town
five months ago. ``Even if the same men are re-elected I want them
to know that they aren't going to govern without the rest of us
being informed.''
   The mayor insists the land was rezoned in 1964, but residents
found a letter from the council to Fayette County building
officials, dated Dec. 8, 1987, that says the council ``has approved
the zoning of Land Lot 203 to be commercial.'' The residents take
that to mean the rezoning was done at about that time.
   There are no signs announcing council meeting times.
   The only sign announcing the September elections is posted on the
1961 Coke machine in Carden's car repair shop every August.
   ``That's the only place it's been posted. The people in Woolsey
that do not know when it's time for an election have not talked to
people in Woolsey or those on the council,'' Zeller said.
   Since 1984, the state has required towns to post election
results. Woolsey has not sent the state any results since then.
   Woolsey's fire, police, water and building inspectors are
provided by Fayette County. Woolsey's officials are not paid and
there is no city budget, city taxes or business license fees.
   Homeowners complained about the zoning flap to the Fayette County
Commission last week but the commissioners said there was nothing
they could do.
   The commissioners invited Zeller and the councilmen but they
declined to attend. Zeller said they didn't want to answer questions
from the floor.
   ``It's a very hostile thing, answering questions from the
floor,'' the mayor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881211-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MuseumThefts     12-11 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Museum Thefts,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Museums Hope Publicity And Security Will Ward Off Thefts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Museums are less secretive about thefts now
as they hope publicity will help recover stolen items and they're
paying more attention to security because one theft could mean a
loss worth millions, officials say.
   Although the annual number of thefts may not be increasing, the
value of the items stolen is, according to Constance Lowenthal,
executive director of the New York-based International Foundation
for Art Research.
   ``Security is something that museums have to think about more and
more,'' she said.
   The foundation promotes the recovery of stolen items through a
directory, published 10 times a year, of items that have been taken.
The publication is distributed internationally to art dealers,
museums, collectors and insurance companies.
   Only 12 percent of the art objects stolen are recovered, she said.
   In just the past month, four items have been taken from two
Philadelphia museums. And an Edouard Manet painting, valued at more
than $1 million, was taken from the Heckscher Museum in Huntington,
N.Y., but later recovered.
   Museums once shied away from publicizing thefts for fear of
scaring off would-be donors. Now, they are beginning to see that
publicity can help recover items, making them ``too hot to handle,''
Lowenthal said.
   She pointed to the Heckscher robbery, in which the remorseful
thief called police and told them where the painting could be
recovered.
   The foundation directory will publish descriptions of the items
taken from the two Philadelphie institutions _ the University Museum
and the Rodin Museum.
   During the early morning of Nov. 11, the University Museum lost
the world's second-largest crystal ball, a clear quartz sphere 10
inches in diameter and weighing 55 pounds, and a 2,000-year-old
Egyptian statuette of Osiris, the god of the underworld. The quartz
orb, carved in the late 19th century for the Empress Dowager of
China, is valued at up to $300,000 and the statuette is worth up to
$45,000.
   A week later, the museum discovered the theft of a Sri Lankan
mask from a hands-on exhibit for the blind, which has since been
closed, said museum spokeswoman Molly Stockdale.
   New security measures were installed and armed campus officers
now patrol the museum at night, she said.
   Lowenthal said a ``very disturbing'' trend also has been for more
violent robberies.
   On Nov. 23, an armed man took a 12-inch bronze head from the
Rodin Museum after handcuffing the unarmed guards. The piece, ``Mask
of the Man With the Broken Nose,'' is valued at more than $75,000.
   Leon J. Perelman, 77, operated the Perelman Toy Museum in
Philadelphia until a robbery in August in which a caretaker was
bound and held at gunpoint by two men. The only items taken in the
robbery were marbles.
   ``I think in my own particular case I had very valuable items
that were worth 10 times the items stolen,'' he said. ``Whoever was
behind this was a collector of marbles. ... This was the kind of
thing (the robbers) were getting for somebody.''
   Perelman closed the museum after the robbery and has sold the
remaining pieces.
   He said unscrupulous art collectors may hire someone to take
selected pieces, which then are hidden for the collector's private
enjoyment.
   ``There are individual collectors who are so obsessed with the
fact they have to own certain things,'' Perelman said.
   Despite the increase in prices for art _ a painting by Pablo
Picasso recently sold in London for $38.5 million _ profit isn't
considered by many to be what prompts thefts.
   ``It's very difficult ... to market an item once it's been
stolen,'' said Ed Able, executive director of the American Museum
Association in Washington.
   After an item is reported stolen, the publicity usually prevents
the robber from selling it openly and receiving a large sum of money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
