<DOCNO> AP881211-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1410EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bowen Bjt   12-11 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bowen, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HHS Chief Says Bush Administration Must Walk `Tight Line' on Health
Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outgoing Health and Human Services
secretary says the Bush administration will have to ``walk a very
tight line'' to avoid cutting the quality of health care in trying
to curb soaring Medicare expenses.
   Dr. Otis R. Bowen said that with a federal budget out of balance,
Medicare cannot escape close scrutiny simply because it is one of
the nation's largest budget items and one of the fastest growing,
particularly the 15 percent annual inflation rate in physician
payments.
   ``At the same time we have to walk a very tight line and make
sure we are not reducing the quality of care and access to care,''
he said in an interview last week. ``It is my judgment that we're
getting close to that level now and we have to be very cautious
about going too deep.''
   Bowen declined to discuss specifics of the final budget the
Reagan administration will submit next month.
   However, department officials have acknowledged previously that
they have agreed to about $6 billion in net reductions in projected
Medicare outlays, mostly by holding down payments to doctors and
hospitals.
   No reductions are proposed in benefits for the 32 million elderly
and disabled Americans served by Medicare, nor does the budget
envision increased charges to beneficiaries.
   Looking beyond the restraints he has agreed to for the next
budget, Bowen said, ``We are getting close to the time where further
ratcheting down could cause some deterioration in the quality of
care and perhaps even access to care.''
   ``The next secretary and the next administration are going to
have some difficult battles with the health care providers and also
maybe even with the senior citizens who are being impacted by it,''
he said.
   ``One of the reasons it's going to be tougher is because of the
massive new numbers of old people that we have coming along,'' said
Bowen, who will be 71 in February.
   He cited statistics projecting that the number of people over 100
years of age will grow from 25,000 to 100,000 in just over a decade.
   Not only will they require more medical attention because of such
an advanced age, Bowen said, those living longer will have used up
their savings and ``might become a bigger burden'' on public
assistance.
   Bowen, a former two-term governor of Indiana who long ago
expressed his desire to return to his home state for a quiet
retirement, said in a wide-ranging interview that his greatest sense
of accomplishment was passage of the catastrophic protection
addition to Medicare that takes effect in January.
   ``Getting the president's approval over the objections of so many
in the Cabinet, that was the tough part,'' said Bowen. ``Once the
president gave his approval, then it became a lot easier to try to
contain the number of additions Congress wanted to add to it.''
   His greatest disappointment, he said, was that the states have
moved too slowly to address medical malpractice insurance problems
that Bowen said could be threatening access to health care in some
regions.
   He said he is not certain the Bush administration should propose
federal legislation to supplant the state's traditional control of
insurance during its first year, ``but I think it's certainly time
to begin talking about it and decide what the parameters of such
legislation should be.''
   On AIDS, he said there still needs to be special emphasis on the
epidemic by federal health officers ``because of the emotional
response of the people. People are scared to death.''
   ``I hesitate to single it out as a disease to be treated
differently from others, but I think as yet it does need to have a
little extra special treatment,'' he said.
   Bowen said he has not been consulted by Bush transition officials
for a recommendation on who should succeed him. But he said he hopes
the incoming president will not view the appointment as a minor one.
   ``When you're talking about a kinder and gentler America, you're
talking about HHS,'' he said of the huge agency that has a larger
budget than the Pentagon and embraces such programs as Social
Security, Medicare and welfare.
   The department also includes the sprawling Public Health Service
umbrella that covers such well-known agencies as the Food and Drug
Administration, the National Institutes of Health and the Centers
for Disease Control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
