<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     12-11 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,000 People Demand Release of Religious Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD GIANSETTO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLOMOUC, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 people demonstrated
peacefully Sunday in this city to demand the release of a leading
religious activist who has been confined to a psychiatric hospital
since October.
   Czechoslovak police arrested one of the organizers but did not
otherwise interfere with the 20-minute protest in a downtown square.
   The demonstrators, who prayed and sang religious songs, demanded
that Augustin Navratil be released from the hospital, located
several miles outside of Olomouc in central Czechoslovakia. Earlier
this year, he launched a petition drive calling for more religious
freedom in his country.
   Navratil, 60, who is widely known in Czechoslovakia and has
repeatedly been interrogated and detained in the past six years, was
confined in the hospital Oct. 28. His petition was signed by 600,000
Czechoslovaks around the country.
   Before the demonstrators met in the Peace Square near the City
Hall and the Monument to the Holy Trinity, a Catholic nun who was
praying on the site was taken by force by plainclothes police into
the hall.
   During the gathering, the demonstrators prayed and circled the
monument, carrying crosses that they kept raised in their hands.
   After a woman's voice speaking through a loudspeaker from the
direction of the City Hall asked the people to ``go back home,''
several plainclothes policemen grabbed a demonstrator, dragged him
to a car and sped off.
   Sources among the demonstrators identified the youth as Michal
Mrtvy, an organizer of the rally. Mrtvy's wife told reporters she
did not know why her husband was taken away but said that three
years ago he was arrested for having distributed religious
literature.
   The sources, who demanded anonymity, said two other organizers,
identified as Pavel Zalesky and Tomas Kopriva, were arrested earlier
this week and have been kept in police custody ever since.
   Another man, who identified himself as Radomir Maly, told
reporters that he was shortly detained on Friday, when police
ordered him not to go to Prague and attend a human rights meeting
there on Saturday.
   Maly said he visited Navratil recently and found him fine. ``He
is free to walk in the hospital and he appears to be well treated,''
Maly told reporters.
   However, Maly said he did not know when Navratil would be
released.
   Thousands of people gathered in Prague on Saturday to demand more
freedom and human rights in Czechoslovakia at the first independent
rally permitted by the communist authorities in nearly 20 years.
   They originally planned the rally, called to mark the 40th
anniversary of ther 1948 Declaration of Human Rights, for Prague's
historic Wenceslas Square.
   Authorities banned the gathering in the city center, but
unexpectedly offered an alternative site about a mile away.
</TEXT>
