<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1520EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrimeBarricades Bjt   12-11 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crime Barricades, Bjt,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighborhoods Afraid Of Crime, Tired Of Traffic</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Florida residents willing to pay extra for a
feeling of security have taken crime and traffic problems into their
own hands, blocking off public streets with barricades and posting
guardhouses.
   A guardhouse is going up in the Andover area in Dade County,
barricades are in place in suburban Miami Shores, roving patrols
operate in the Hammock Oaks subdivision, and a dozen road barriers
have been placed in Fort Lauderdale's Riverside section. Residents
often voluntarily raise taxes for such measures.
   The barricades, a response to muggings, purse snatchings and
break-ins, have been adopted primarily by older, well-to-do
neighborhoods bordered by less affluent areas or commercial strips.
   ``The disturbing fact of this, I suppose, in the worst-case
scenario there's the medieval idea of a walled city,'' said William
Tilson, an associate professor of architecture who specializes in
urban design at the University of Florida. ``It's kind of ironic in
a society that seems to be so concerned about information and
networks that we're often myopic in other actions.''
   Street barriers have been adopted by communities across the
nation as buffers against crime, in St. Louis for example, and to
encourage bicycle and pedestrian traffic, such as those in Davis,
Calif.
   Barricades ``are a response to a crime condition that's gotten
out of hand,'' Tilson said. ``They're seen as perhaps the most
economical or the most expedient ways of dealing with a problem that
presents itself immediately.''
   The prestigious Palm, Hibiscus and Star islands in Biscayne Bay
have opted for guardhouses, where the license plate numbers of
visitors are copied down.
   Miami Shores blocked 18 intersections with barrels and stop signs
in June and has seen a 17 percent reduction in crime for the village
as a whole and 20 percent in the barricaded zones, said Mayor Spero
Canton.
   The village of 9,600 people north of downtown Miami ranges from
lower middle-class homes to affluent country club homes and bayside
villas.
   ``We live about a half-mile from some pretty tough areas of Dade
County, so it seems that when these crack addicts or drug users look
for money, they look to a neighborhood with money,'' Canton said.
   Attorney Peter Kircher, a Miami Shores resident on a committee
opposed to barricades, considers them ludicrous and the expense
``utter stupidity.''
   ``It started out as a partial solution to a problem and then it
became a solution to everything,'' he said. ``Increasing property
values. Decreasing traffic. Crime. Name the problem, we will solve
it with barricades.''
   Kircher has urged his village council to remove the barricades,
but council members have refused, saying residents have a right to
block off their streets to discourage criminals from cruising their
neighborhoods.
   In unincorported Dade County, five special taxing districts have
been formed and four applications are pending from residents willing
to pay extra property taxes for street closings, guard gates and
extra patrols.
   The Andover area, where streets are lined by royal palms and
property values range from $125,000 to $300,000, will open its
guardhouse Jan. 1. About 475 residents will pay $380 each next year
and $150-$175 a year afterward for their new district.
   ``We're not foolish enough to believe it's going to be a panacea
of all our ills,'' said Don Grate, a retired schoolteacher and
president of the Andover Civic Association. ``We think the value of
property will go up knowing you have more security. People like to
feel they have some semblance of security.''
   Fort Lauderdale Mayor Robert Cox said, ``The perception of safety
is almost as important as the safety itself.''
   ``What do you have when you've barricaded off all the good
areas?'' asked Hubert Williams, president of the Washington-based
Police Foundation think tank. ``If the sense of community is
predicated on class discrimination, that kind of thing would be
diametrically opposed to our highest democratic principles.''
   He also mentioned concern for the right to use public
thoroughfares.
   William Wilbanks, a criminal justice professor at Miami's Florida
International University, said that such security measure will
``displace crime in areas that are not too well protected. That will
probably mean poorer communities.''
</TEXT>
