<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-11 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soggy Sunday For The Southeast States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell over much of the Southeast on Sunday, light snow was
scattered over the center of the nation, and up to 14 inches of snow
accumulated near the lower Great Lakes.
   Low pressure over the north-central Gulf of Mexico generated the
rain over the Southeast, with showers extending from the lower
Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms, some of them strong, produced locally
heavy rain in northern Florida.
   In the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, Apalachicola, Fla., got 0.98
of an inch of rain.
   Snow and sleet extended over parts of Arkansas and northern
Mississippi and were expected to spread into northern Alabama.
   Rain over South Carolina also was expected to change to sleet and
snow as cold air flowed in, and a winter storm warning was issued
for the mountains of South Carolina.
   Squalls produced snow around the lower Great Lakes through the
morning. In 24 hours, 14 inches of snow accumulated at the western
New York state town of Sodus and Sherman, N.Y., received 12 inches.
   A weak storm system produced light snow in the central part of
the nation including parts of South Dakota, Iowa, Missouri, Kansas
and Nebraska. Little Sioux, Neb., had 4 inches of snow by early
afternoon.
   Fog and drizzle spread over much of the West.
   By early afternoon, temperatures remained below freezing from the
northern and central Plains to the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast. Temperatures were only in the single digits or below zero in
Minnesota, eastern North Dakota, northeastern South Dakota, northern
Iowa, northwestern Wisconsin, Upper Michigan, northern Lower
Michigan, upstate New York and northern New England.
   Readings were in the 70s and 80s across southern and central
Florida and in the 60s and 70s in southern California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees below zero at Limestone, Maine, to 82 at Vero Beach and West
Palm Beach, Fla. Sunday morning's official low was 25 degrees below
zero at International Falls, Minn.
   For Monday, rain was forecast from Louisiana to the southern
Atlantic Coast, changing to snow from northern Alabama to the
southern Appalachians. Light snow or snow showers were forecast over
the upper half of the Mississippi Valley and western sections of the
Great Lakes. Showers were forecast in the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from the middle and
upper Mississippi Valley to the middle and northern Atlantic Coast,
including below 20 degrees from northeastern Minnesota to the
northern Atlantic Coast, and in the single digits across northern
New England and upstate New York; above 50 from the Pacific Coast
through much of Arizona and New Mexico to the Texas coast and across
southern Georgia and northern Georgia, including highs in the 60s
and 70s in southern California and southern Arizona, in the 60s
across central Florida, and in the 70s in southern Florida.
</TEXT>
