<HEAD>Former Philippines President Remains Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
remained in guarded but stable condition on Sunday, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   Beyond the brief condition report, ``the physicians won't be
talking again this weekend. They'll have a statement at noon
Monday,'' said St. Francis Medical Center nursing supervisor Elsie
Katano.
   Aides say Marcos, 71, experienced congestive heart failure Friday
after learning his eldest daughter, Imee Manotoc, was experiencing
complications during childbirth in Morocco, where she lives.
   The Philippines consul general in Hawaii, Thomas Gomez, says he
thinks Marcos is faking illness to avoid arraignment in federal
court in New York on federal racketeering charges, which allege he
plundered millions of dollars from the Philippine treasury.
   A New York cardiologist who examined Marcos last month for a
federal judge in New York reported that although Marcos suffers
various ailments, he is well enough to travel.
   Imelda Marcos angrily denied charges that her husband is faking.
   ``I'm fighting for the survival of my husband,'' she told
reporters.
   Hospital officials on Saturday quoted Dr. Calvin Wong, the
cardiologist attending Marcos, as saying tests confirmed that Marcos
had ``weakened heart muscles.'' Wong could not be reached to
elaborate.
