<HEAD>Israel Sends Rescue Team; Armenians Mourn In Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, ``We have...'' to ADD
background on hijacking. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The relief...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 42-member Israeli rescue team headed by an
army general left Sunday in an air force jet for Yerevan in Soviet
Armenia to help search for earthquake survivors.
   An army spokesman said two other planes would leave for the
Soviet Union on Monday with a 46-member medical team, equipment and
4{ tons of medical supplies for victims of Wednesday's quake that
killed tens of thousands of people.
   The relief effort marked the second time this month that Israel
has rendered humanitarian assistance to the Soviets which broke
diplomatic relations with Israel in 1967 when Israel captured Arab
lands.
   ``We have no intention of building political achievements on such
tragic events,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Allon Liel said in a
telephone interview. ``I must state, though, that the atmosphere
created following this and the hijack incident last week, is a warm
and friendly one.''
   On Dec. 2, four people hijacked a cargo plane in the Soviet Union
and forced the crew to fly them to Israel. After a series of unusual
diplomatic contacts between the two countries, Israel allowed Soviet
authorities to come to Tel Aviv to claim the plane and the hijackers.
   The relief team is headed by Gen. Aharon Vardi who is in charge
of the army's civil defense unit. Traveling with him are specially
trained experts in operating heavy cranes, several doctors, and an
Alsatian shepherd named Tim, who is trained to sniff people under
rubble and wore a red Star of David on a white chest cloth.
   Vardi said the group had enough camping equipment to remain up to
three weeks, if the Soviets are able to provide them with enough
trucks, gas and water.
   In Jerusalem, hundreds of grieving Armenians wearing black
armbands and veils marched in silence through the streets of
Jerusalem's Old City on Sunday to mourn the earthquake victims.
   Also at the demonstration were Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek and
Natan Sharansky, a former Soviet prisoner and human rights activist.
   Many wept at St. James Cathedral during a candlelight prayer
service presided over by Archbishop Karekin Kazandjian of
Jerusalem's 2,000 member Armenian church.
