<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Tibet 1stLd-Writethru a0677 12-11 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Tibet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buddhist Monk Killed, 13 Wounded In Tibetan Protests, China Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police searching hotel rooms,
account of wounded Danish woman, other foreigners. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities imposed tight security in the Tibetan
capital and searched foreigners' hotel rooms Sunday, a day after
police fired on independence activists in a central square, Western
travelers said.
   China said Sunday that a Buddhist monk was killed and 13 people
were wounded when police fired into a crowd during the demonstration
in Lhasa. Western travelers said they believed two people were
killed, and another foreign traveler said a Tibetan reported seeing
four bodies at a hospital.
   It was not immediately possible to reconcile the casualty figures.
   The clash on Saturday was the third bloody confrontation in the
remote region between authorities and anti-Chinese protesters since
October 1987.
   Tourists said Chinese police were looking for foreigners caught
in the protest near the Jokhang Temple, one of the holiest sites of
Tibetan Buddhism.
   A Dutch woman wounded in the left shoulder reported ``complete
panic'' after the shooting began.
   ``Everybody started running. I heard the bullets skimming past my
head _ shoo, shoo,'' said Christa Meindersma, of Amsterdam, in a
telephone interview from her hotel room in Lhasa.
   ``I felt a sting in my arm, but I didn't realize it was a
bullet,'' said Ms. Meindersma. ``The soldiers were running after us.
I ran into a Tibetan courtyard and I said, `I'm wounded,' and I
fainted.''
   Ms. Meindersma, who said she had been in Lhasa since September
studying Tibetan, said she refused to stay in a hospital where she
was treated because police wanted to question her and take her
picture. She said police also searched her hotel room.
   She said police searched the rooms of other foreign tourists.
   A large group of Tibetans prayed on Sunday near scattered pools
of blood left from Saturday's clash in the city's central
markeplace, said a Frenchman reached by telephone in Lhasa.
   ``They placed candles and little white tissues on the blood in
the same way they do for the Buddhas in their temples,'' said the
26-year-old Frenchman, who identified himself only as Thierry.
   He said there was no new violence by midday Sunday, when about
1,000 police drove through the city and others patrolled the market
on foot. He said soldiers with guns also stood guard from rooftops
overlooking the market.
   A traveler speaking on condition of anonymity said by telephone
from Lhasa that a Tibetan who went to the hospital to give blood for
the wounded saw four bodies.
   On Sunday, activists were distributing leaflets in Tibetan and
English calling for an end to Chinese rule over Tibet, the Frenchman
said.
   Two witnesses to Saturday's events said Buddhist monks told them
there would be another demonstration Sunday, but later efforts to
reach the remote region by phone and telex were unsuccessful.
   The clash Saturday began when 30 Tibetans, identified by the
Xinhua News Agency as monks and nuns, marched into the market
carrying the banned Tibetan flag to commemorate the 40th anniversary
of the U.N. Declaration on Human Rights. The protesters, dressed in
street clothes and face masks, demanded an end to 38 years of
Chinese communist rule over the Himalayan region.
   The nationally televised evening news said police ``were forced
to fire'' during Saturday's unrest when ``some troublemakers refused
to heed a warning and threw stones and bottles at police.''
   The official Xinhua News Agency said that of the 13 injured, two
were seriously hurt. It gave no details and did not say if they were
demonstrators.
   Another Dutch woman who witnessed the clash, Lucia Dezries, said
a crowd of Tibetans surged toward the demonstrators and began
stoning the security forces, who opened fire. She said it was not
clear whether the stone-throwing or shooting began first.
   Ms. Dezries said she saw two people lying in pools of blood and
was told they were dead.
   The Chinese government claims Tibet has been part of China since
the 13th century. Many Tibetans, however, say they were independent
during most of that time and were ruled by a Buddhist theocracy
headed by the Dalai Lama, who had both civil and religious authority.
   Chinese communist troops moved into Tibet in 1950 and put down an
uprising nine years later during which the Dalai Lama fled to India.
</TEXT>
