<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-Gorbachev     12-11 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Gorbachev,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Exhorts Rescue Workers, Criticizes New Buildings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, standing in the
rubble in the earthquake-ruined city of Spitak, told rescue workers
Sunday they must race to bury the dead before an epidemic strikes
and takes more lives.
   In 20 minutes of remarks shown to the nation on the television
evening news, Gorbachev also promised Armenians an investigation
into why new buildings collapsed in Wednesday's quake while older
structures remained standing.
   He said that once the rescue and cleanup are completed, a
government commission will look into that question.
   ``Why did buildings from three years ago collapse while those
built with three or five stories under (former Soviet Premier Nikita
S.) Khrushchev are still standing?'' he said in an angry tone.
   Soviet buildings are notoriously poorly constructed, but the
public admission of this by a top Soviet official is rare.
   In an emotional exchange, a man in the crowd that surrounded
Gorbachev on a Spitak street demanded to know why scientists did not
predicted the earthquake, which has killed at least 40,000 people
according to official estimates.
   ``We also are making such demands,'' the Soviet leader told the
man. But he added, ``So far, nowhere in the world do they have
methods to predict'' earthquakes.
   He said Health Minister Yevgeny I. Chazov had advised him that
the weather conditions in the disaster area would create a threat of
an epidemic seven days after the earthquake. Bodies buried under the
rubble must be removed to avoid an outbreak, he said.
   Gorbachev told the rescuers that doctors and health officials
have devised emergency measures in case an epidemic strikes. He did
not elaborate.
   The Kremlin chief did not specify what kind of epidemic might
break out. But destruction of urban water supplies and pollution
from decaying corpses can spread deadly diseases such as typhoid and
dysentery.
   Later on the broadcast, Gorbachev spoke in the Armenian capital
of Yerevan with a Soviet television correspondent who asked about
the dispute between Armenians and Azerbaijanis over the
Nagorno-Karabakh district of Azerbaijan. Armenians have been
pressing for the annexation of the region, most of whose people are
ethnic Armenians.
   Gorbachev, raising his hands for emphasis and speaking in an
angry tone, accused ``provocateurs'' pushing for control of
Nagorno-Karabakh of using the tragic consequences of the earthquake
to create instability.
   He said some activists accused authorities of planning to take
children orphaned in the earthquake out of Armenia. Gorbachev
angrily denied this was planned and said: ``What kind of morals do
those people have?''
   ``They don't need Karabakh. They are waging a battle for power,
and they must be stopped,'' he said.
   Gorbachev and the rest of the leadership have rejected the
annexation demand. The dispute between Armenians and Azerbaijanis
over the issue has led to violence that has killed about 60 people.
   In the interview, Gorbachev praised the outpouring of assistance
from throughout the Soviet Union for earthquake victims.
   ``We are proud of all our people,'' he said. ``What immense moral
strength they have!''
   The priority in the rescue now, he said, is to save people still
trapped under the piles of crumbled concrete.
   ``First and foremost we must help to clear these piles of rubble,
where there are still many people alive. Because people are being
freed there every day. I have met some of them. So the first task,
the first thing being done, is to save those who are still alive.
   ``Those who have perished must also be got out as befits human
beings, given a funeral,'' Gorbachev said.
</TEXT>
