<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-11 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Helena Symphony Chorale has given new
meaning to the idea of a singing telegram.
   The chorale recently began a ``rent-a-choir'' program, giving
people a chance to hire any number of singers to perform at an event.
   ``We can arrange anything from a solo to the whole chorale,''
says Dave Buness, chorale director.
   The rent-a-choir is pretty well booked for the holiday season, he
said, but stressed that the group's repertoire goes beyond Christmas
carols.
   ``This isn't just a Christmas activity,'' he said. ``We'd be glad
to come perform any time at all.''
   Renting the choir costs a minimum of $35. The money goes to the
Helena Symphony Society, to help pay for the chorale's annual trip
to an out-of-state music educators' convention.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dating service here had tried advertising in
newspapers and magazines, on television and through direct mail. But
now it's on a roll. It's on many rolls, in fact, rolls of the kind
of paper found in rest rooms.
   Jerry Womack had ads for ``Modern Love'' printed on individual
squares of toilet paper and then distributed rolls in bars and
restaurants ``where people in the 25 to 50 age range frequent.''
   ``Everybody has pens with their name on it,'' Womack said. ``I
wanted to see how far I could push the limits.''
   Womack said he thought of the idea during a meeting with Craig
King, an advertising representative for Shaw-Barton, of Coshocton,
Ohio, which was pushing calendar ads.
   He said Innovative Paper Products of Roseville, Ill., printed
about 200 ``Modern Love'' rolls for about $3 each. The ads have
generated about 120 calls in two months of distribution, making them
a success, Womack said.
   King said he thought Womack was joking when he first mentioned
toilet paper, but now mentions the option to other customers.
   ``They're amused by it, but most people don't think it's for
them,'' he said. ``Some people think it might give a derogatory name
to their product. Not everyone wants to have their name on toilet
paper.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilmington College is beginning the
second year of an offbeat student recruiting campaign that features
a small arctic animal called a lemming.
   The college reports the campaign is highly successful, either
despite or because of its use of humor in a matter young people take
very seriously.
   College spokesman Ray Wojda noted that the traditional student
recruiting features ``five nerdy kids'' standing in front of a
stately old campus building.
   By contrast, the small Quaker-related school's campaign features
a cartoon rodent who carries a Lemming State pennant, wears official
Lemming State sneakers _ ``perfect for following the crowd and
jumping to conclusions,'' the ad says _ and has eyes that are
bloodshot from straining to see the blackboard from the back of a
lecture auditorium.
   Lemmings, which look like gophers, have a destructive herd
instinct that causes them occasionally to migrate toward the sea,
where they often drown.
   The Wilmington campaign promises the college is for those who
``would rather be an active participant in your education than a
bystander.''
   Results of the campaign have ``far exceeded our expectations,''
Wojda said. Enrollment rose to a capacity 825 from 759 last fall.
Applications increased 15 percent, and entering students' scores on
the American College Test were the highest in 12 years, Wojda said.
   The ads, which were designed by the Cincinnati advertising firm
of Sullivan & Findsen, were so successful that Wilmington is trying
the humorous approach again in its annual fund-raising campaign,
featuring a parody newspaper.
</TEXT>
