<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-BakkerService     12-11 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Bakker Service,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Rails Against Media; Urges Forgiveness For Accusers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker railed against the
news media but urged followers of his New Covenant Church to forgive
his accusers Sunday in his first public remarks since being indicted
on fraud and conspiracy charges.
   ``If the news media wasn't the biggest money-maker today, would
they still pay people $1 million to lie and tell stories?'' he said
during a 20-minute message to about 400 followers. ``The love of
money is the root of all evil.''
   ``They ask us, `Why don't you attack your enemies?''' Bakker
said, his voice rising. ``The Devil wants me to renounce my
salvation and attack, attack, attack. The Bible says `Love your
enemies.'''
   ``I'm not going to lift a finger to attack my enemies. I'm not
going to lift a finger to vindicate me,'' Bakker said. ``That will
put cold chills down your enemy's spine.''
   Bakker also talked about his reaction to being fingerprinted and
having his mugshot taken at the federal courthouse in Charlotte.
   ``I looked up at all those wanted posters and I thought, `No one
is smiling _ so I smiled,''' Bakker said. ``If I'm going to be on
the walls of post offices, I'm going to smile.''
   Bakker did not allow reporters inside the converted skating rink
where his New Covenant Church holds Sunday services. However, some
of his remarks could be heard through the door.
   Bakker has declined interviews since his indictment last Monday
on 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy. He and three of his former
associates were indicted after a 16-month federal grand jury
investigation of the PTL television ministry.
   Bakker, 48, and Richard Dortch, 57, his former top deputy at PTL,
were accused of diverting more than $4 million of their followers'
money to support their own ``lavish and extravagant'' lifestyles.
They and the others are expected to appear Thursday before U.S.
Magistrate Paul Taylor.
   Bakker resigned from PTL in March 1987 after admitting money was
paid to buy the silence of a woman with whom he had sex.
   Meanwhile, PTL, which filed for reorganization under federal
bankruptcy law in June 1987, goes on the auction block with its
Heritage USA theme park Monday at the order of a bankruptcy judge.
   Analysts say it's unlikely creditors will get more than a
fraction of the $130 million they're owed.
   It will be the second time in a month that court-appointed
trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton will try to auction the 2,200-acre
property, which includes a 500-room hotel, a water park, a
television studio and a 2,000-seat church.
   The only certain bidder, Toronto businessman Stephen Mernick, has
let it be known he intends to offer a total of less than $70 million
cash. A month ago, he said he would pay $115 million, $50 million of
it cash.
   If the top bid doesn't satisfy U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus
Reynolds, the judge might shut down PTL and sell it piece by piece.
   As Bakker and his wife, Tammy Faye, entered the building Sunday,
he briefly talked about reports that more than 30 television
ministries were under investigation by the Internal Revenue Service.
   ``They fear evangelism,'' he said.
   Bakker, in introducing a fellow preacher at the service, made an
apparent reference to former associate John Wesley Fletcher, who was
quoted by Penthouse magazine as saying he had a homosexual
relationship with Bakker.
   ``I've learned people I gave $100,000 to weren't my friends,'' he
said. ``It's wonderful to know you have friends. I'm talking about
people who stick with you through thick and thin.''
</TEXT>
