<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarijuanaFire     12-11 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marijuana Fire,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bodies, Weapons Found In Fire At Idaho Pot-Growing Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONNERS FERRY, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two badly burned bodies, dozens of
weapons and the largest marijuana growing operation ever found in
Idaho were discovered after a fire leveled a ranch house.
   The weapons included machine guns, handguns and rifles.
   ``We even found what we think is a 105mm shell for a cannon,''
said Wayne Longo, regional manager of the Idaho Bureau of Narcotics.
``Some of the weapons even had bayonets on them.''
   Several booby traps were found on the property, and state agents
wore bulletproof vests while they searched the grounds Saturday,
Longo said. The investigation continued Sunday.
   Authorities found the bodies while examining the wreckage of the
house that burned Friday night on a 40-acre ranch near Bonners Ferry
in northern Idaho.
   ``We can't even tell if they're male or female,'' said Longo.
``We're calling a pathologist to do that.''
   He said investigators don't know if the two died in the fire or
before it started. Sheriff's deputies said no identities had been
determined by Sunday afternooon.
   Authorities were unable to locate the owners of the ranch, David
and Helen Ashley. Deputies have records of at least five adults
living in the house, Longo said.
   Next to the house is an old, dilapidated barn, Longo said. But
inside, authorities found a building withing the building,
containing ``the largest and most sophisticated marijuana-growing
operation ever seen in Idaho.''
   Longo estimated the structure contained at least 1,000 marijuana
plants. ``We found plants in every single stage of growth, from
seedlings to harvested ones, drying out and ready to sell,'' he said.
   The cause of the fire was not determined by Sunday.
</TEXT>
