<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Quake-Reagan     12-11 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Reagan,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Visit Soviet Embassy To Sign Condolence Book</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A solemn President Reagan visited the Soviet
Embassy on Sunday and signed a book of condolences for victims of
the Armenian earthquake, writing that he spoke for the American
people in stating, ``You are in our thoughts and prayers.''
   First lady Nancy Reagan accompanied the president and also signed
the book, writing, ``What a terrible human tragedy. Our deepest
sympathy.''
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin told the president, ``We are
deeply moved by your direct participation in our disaster, Mr.
President, and also by the participation of the American people.''
   The Reagans visited the embassy while on their way to the
historic 19th century Pension Building for the taping of an annual
television special on Christmas at the White House.
   Upon their arrival at the embassy, the Reagans walked up a
red-carpeted inner stairway accompanied by the ambassador and his
wife, and stopped briefly to view a display of photographs from the
earthquake area.
   Reagan shook his head in dismay from time to time, and Mrs.
Reagan appeared close to tears as the ambassador described the
plight of the earthquake victims.
   ``It's terrible, it's terrible, an appalling thing,'' the
ambassador said. ``This whole region, this whole area, was
destroyed.''
   The Reagans apparently murmured a few words in response, which
reporters standing across the room were unable to hear.
   The president and first lady then moved to the book, which lay
open on a table covered with a red cloth bordered in black. Mrs.
Reagan sat first and signed, and was followed by the president,
whose message in full read, ``I speak for all our people when I say
we share your sorrow. You are in our thoughts and prayers.'' He
signed the message Ronald Reagan.
   Later at the Pension Building, Reagan was asked about U.S. aid to
the earthquake victims and replied, ``We immediately offered and
they accepted and I think four of our planes have landed.''
   Asked whether discussions with the Soviets about the aid program
were continuing, he nodded and replied, ``At the State Department.''
   The embassy issued a statement saying that according to
preliminary data, the number of dead is estimated at 40,000-45,000,
with about 500,000 people left homeless.
</TEXT>
