<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru   12-11 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0699,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Snubs Communist-led Union, Meets With Moderates</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs to move up snub of communist-led union.
Pick up 5th pvs, `Walesa made...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLINE ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa visited the
headquarters of four French national unions Sunday but snubbed the
largest labor federation, the communist-led General Confederation of
Labor.
   Walesa, making his first foreign visit in seven years, thanked
the four unions for their support and urged East and West Europe to
come together in peace.
   ``Something is moving in Poland, something is moving in Eastern
Europe,'' Walesa said. ``Our Europe should rejoin yours. We want to
rejoin peacefully, intelligently but with respect for the identity
and culture of each party.''
   The powerful General Confederation of Labor, currently leading a
strike that has snarled public transit in Paris for weeks, backed
the 1981 martial-law crackdown on Solidarity by Polish leader
Wojciech Jaruzelski. Over the years, it has usually followed
Moscow's lead on international policy.
   Walesa made a round of visits to the smaller French Democratic
Confederation of Labor, the French Confederation of Christian Labor,
the Workers Force and the General Confederation of Cadres, thanking
them for their support over the years.
   Although union membership figures in France are unreliable,
independent experts estimate about one-fourth of union members in
the country belong to the communist confederation, including many
non-communists.
   Walesa made only one public reference to the communist-led
confederation, saying its secretary-general, Henri Krasucki, had not
contacted him when visiting Poland. He joked that he might have lost
his address while cleaning out his pockets in anticipation of being
searched by Polish authorities. ``Perhaps I would also lose the
address in a similar situation,'' Walesa added.
   Krasucki said Saturday he found the Polish union leader's
three-day itinerary ``very significant'' and said Walesa was meeting
only leaders of unions who ``are refusing to take action and signing
accords on the backs of French workers which destroy the social
achievements of a half-century.''
   The other four unions recently signed an agreement with the Paris
transit authority that the confederation denounced as a sell-out of
workers' interests.
   Walesa was in Paris at the invitation of President Francois
Mitterrand for Saturday's celebrations marking the 40th anniversary
of the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights. He and Soviet human rights
activist Andrei Sakharov met for the first time Saturday. The two
men are both Nobel Peace Prize winners _ Walesa in 1983 and Sakharov
in 1975.
   Bronislaw Geremek, a top Solidarity aide and Walesa's personal
adviser, said both men agreed the Soviet Union and Poland must make
more progress on human rights before Walesa would be willing to
participate in a proposed human rights conference in Moscow.
   Geremek said the first signs of hope for dialogue with Polish
authorities came only recently when Walesa appeared on
government-controlled television for a three-hour debate _ media
exposure which he has long been denied.
   ``Maybe we can finish this year with progress,'' Geremek said.
   Walesa has started each day at a Mass sung in Polish at the
Polish Roman Catholic community's 17th century domed church off the
Place de la Concorde.
   On Sunday he met Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, the Polish-born
Roman Catholic archbishop of Paris, who described Walesa as living
proof that ``freedom is the most precious of all the qualities in
the world, because nothing can bind a man who is free to think, love
and forgive.''
   Sakharov and his wife Yelena Bonner spent a quiet and private
Sunday shopping and lunching at an Italian restaurant.
   Neither Sakharov nor Walesa have conducted high-profile visits,
nor have they publicly criticized the Polish or Soviet governments.
They have limited brief statements to general human rights issues
and appeals for help for earthquake victims in Armenia.
</TEXT>
