<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OrbisonService     12-11 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orbison Service,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Eulogized As One Who `Touched Millions'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock 'n' roll pioneer Roy Orbison was
eulogized Sunday as a singer who ``touched the lives of millions''
around the world.
   About 75 friends and music industry associates attended a
30-minute memorial service for Orbison, the performer known for hits
such as ``Oh, Pretty Woman,'' ``Only the Lonely'' and ``Crying.''
   ``He became a legend in his own time,'' the Rev. Larry Gilmore
said in his eulogy to Orbison, who died of a heart attack Tuesday at
52.
   ``He touched the lives of millions throughout the world,''
Gilmore told those gathered at College Heights Baptist Church, about
30 miles northeast of Nashville. Orbison worshiped at the church.
   ``His ability in music is unquestioned,'' Gilmore said. ``A world
has benefited from what he shared in the music industry.''
   It was the first memorial service for Orbison, who was known for
his ever-present sunglasses, dark attire and ebony pompadour during
his 30-year singing career.
   A similar gathering, termed a ``celebration of life,'' is
scheduled for Tuesday night at a nightclub in Los Angeles, the name
of which is being released only to friends and associates.
   Orbison lived in Malibu, Calif., for the past four years. Prior
to that, he had lived in Nashville for 30 years.
   He was enjoying a career comeback at the time of his death as a
member of the Traveling Wilburys whose album of that name is one of
the top selling in the country. Other members of the group are Bob
Dylan, ex-Beatle George Harrison and Tom Petty.
   Among those attending the memorial Sunday were Orbison's brother,
Sam, and one of his three sons, Wesley. The mourners sat quietly
showing little emotion.
   ``I know that he would want us to have a time of thanksgiving,''
Gilmore told them in the eulogy.
   ``Roy didn't like funerals,'' Gilmore said. ``He detested them.''
   Orbison's body was flown Saturday to Los Angeles. Barbara, his
widow, flew to Los Angeles on Wednesday from her native Germany,
where she was visiting friends when the singer died near Nashville
while visiting his mother.
   A private burial was planned.
</TEXT>
