<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwayKillings     12-11 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Killings,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Developing Suspects, Sixth Body Identified as Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Sunday they are
developing a list of possible suspects in a series of related
slayings in southeastern Massachusetts, and that a sixth female body
was found over the weekend.
   District Attorney Ronald Pina said informants are providing
valuable information.
   ``We have a list of potential suspects,'' Pina said. ``There are
people who are known to do things like this and there are people who
are giving us some information.''
   He spoke at a news conference at the site where the body was
found the previous day, in a wooded area about a quarter mile from
Interstate 195 in Dartmouth. Nearby, police were still collecting
parts of the badly decomposed body.
   The remains, found by hunters in a gravel pit and still
unidentified Sunday, was determined to be the sixth female body
found since July in within a few miles of one another outside this
fishing port of 98,000 people. Pina has said the five bodies found
up until Saturday were likely the victim of the same killer or
killers.
   Investigators have identified three of the bodies as women
between the ages of 25 and 36 who had ties to New Bedford's Weld
Square neighborhood, known for prostitution and drug sales.
   Pina said the sixth woman could not definitely be linked to the
others, but was partly clad like the others.
   The sixth body appeared to have been in the woods longer than any
of the others, possibly since last spring, Pina said.
   An autopsy was scheduled for Monday, and police continued
searching the wooded area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
