<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Protest     12-11 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Protest,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young People March Against Government, Break Windows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 young people staged an
anti-government march after a Mass in Gdansk and threw stones at a
police station Sunday, the official PAP news agency said.
   The agency said the predominantly teen-age demonstrators chanted,
``There is No Freedom Without Solidarity,'' and ``Down with the
Commune'' after a service at St. Brygida's Church, a stronghold of
the banned Solidarity independent union movement.
   The youth threw stones at a police station and broke windows,
then dispersed when special riot police squadrons arrived, PAP said.
   Joanna Wojciechowska, a Solidarity spokeswoman in Gdansk, said
about 300 teen-agers marched after Mass around the city's Old Town
section with virtually no police interference.
   She said older Solidarity activists did not know the unorganized
group and were trying to get the young people to end their protest,
but she said the teen-agers were encouraged by the fact that no
police were present.
   ``It was a case of youthful aggression against police which could
not be stopped,'' she said.
   Only after nearly all the station's windows were broken did riot
police come to chase away the marchers, she said.
   Solidarity, the first independent union federation in the Soviet
bloc, was crushed with the imposition of martial law in 1981 and
banned in 1982.
</TEXT>
