<HEAD>Reagan Has `Bittersweet' Thoughts On Last Christmas Season In White
House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Sunday that approaching
his last Christmas season in the White House is ``a kind of mixed,
bittersweet thing'' as he prepares to return to California after his
term ends Jan. 20.
   Reagan was asked about his feelings as he and his wife, Nancy,
took part in the taping of the seventh annual NBC television
special, ``Christmas in Washington.''
   ``It has to be a kind of mixed, bittersweet thing,'' he said.
``We have to say goodbye to a lot of people we are going to miss. On
the other hand, we look forward to being home.''
   The Reagans will spend Christmas day in Los Angeles, where they
will live after the president leaves office, but Mrs. Reagan has
said they plan a family Christmas celebration at the White House on
Dec. 22, before they leave for the holiday.
