<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Emperor     12-11 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Emperor,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Reported Nearly Comatose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was almost completely comatose
Sunday after several days of heavy internal bleeding, news reports
said.
   National newspapers quoted unidentified palace sources as saying
the 87-year-old emperor's heavy bleeding this past week and the
resulting loss of blood pressure damaged his liver and kidneys, and
palace officials have said his brain has been damaged.
   ``According to agency sources, the emperor now appears to be
almost completely comatose,'' said the Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's
largest newspaper. ``His body responds to physical stimulus, but
even when his eyes are open he now completely fails to respond to
people calling his name.''
   Hirohito has been suffering from internal bleeding since his
health suddenly worsened nearly three months ago. During that time
he has received 52.9 pints of blood.
   Palace officials have said the bleeding appears to be near his
upper intestine, where he underwent an intestinal bypass operation
last year. The Yomiuri on Sunday quoted palace officials as saying
the bleeding may have spread to his stomach wall.
   Palace officials continued to refuse to comment on news reports
that the emperor has cancer.
   Under the constitution, Hirohito has no political power but
serves as a symbol of the unity of Japan.
</TEXT>
