<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan-Talks 1stLd-Writethru a0727 12-11 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets To Hold More Talks With Afghan Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with report of Soviet proposal
for direct talks with Iran-based rebels. Pick up 6th pvs, `During
his...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high Soviet official will meet soon
with Pakistan-based Afghan rebels for more peace talks, and Moscow
has proposed direct talks with the guerrillas' Iran-based allies,
rebel leaders said.
   A spokesman for the rebels in Pakistan, Burhannudin Rabbani, said
their meeting with Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Yuri Vorontsov
would take place in the next two weeks. Rabbani spoke in a telephone
interview from Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
   A Pakistan government official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, confirmed the meeting would take place in Islamabad. He
did not say when.
   Rabbani denied news reports that the rebels would accept an
international peace conference proposed by the Soviet and Afghan
governments. ``We reject this conference. It is between us and the
Russians,'' he said.
   The seven-party guerrilla alliance, supported by the United
States and Pakistan, negotiated with the Soviets from Dec. 3 to 5 in
Taif, Saudi Arabia. The private meeting was the first between the
Soviets and representatives of the anti-communist rebels since
Soviet troops marched into Afghanistan in 1979.
   The Soviet Union has also offered to hold direct talks with
leaders of the Afghan resistance based in Iran, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency of Iran reported Sunday.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus, quoted a spokesman for
the Iran-based fundamentalist rebel alliance as saying ``After 10
years of occupation, the Soviets were finally forced to accept that
the Afghan people and the Mujahedeen (rebels) have a major role and
have agreed to talks.''
   The spokesman said that the Iran-based alliance was studying the
Soviet offer and had not yet made a decision whether to accept, the
television broadcast said.
   Most of the fighting against the Soviet troops in Afghanistan has
been conducted by the Pakistan-based rebels, but the Iran-based
rebels have conducted separate operations.
   The news agency said a delegation from the Pakistan-based
alliance was due in Tehran for consultations, but it did not say
when.
   During his recent trip to New York, Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev called for an international peace conference on
Afghanistan and a cease-fire.
   The Soviet Union, which has withdrawn half its 100,000 troops
under a U.N. accord, recently suspended the withdrawal after
complaining that Pakistan and the United States were still arming
the rebels, who have continued fighting.
   ``There is no room for a cease-fire,'' said Rabbani. ``The
Russians must move from Afghanistan.''
   He said Vorontsov assured the Afghan resistance leaders that the
Soviets were ``ready to go'' from Afghanistan.
   The rebels repeatedly have called for the removal of Afghan
President Najib and the disbanding of his Marxist People's
Democratic Party.
   At the talks in Saudi Arabia, Vorontsov reportedly refused to
make any commitments about Najib's future, but Rabbani said the
Soviet official did not close the doors to possible changes in the
Kabul government.
   ``He said everything can be discussed,'' said Rabbani.
   The resistance leader said the most significant outcome of the
direct talks was Moscow's tacit recognition of the Moslem insurgents.
   ``Before, the Russians did not recognize the rebels,'' said
Rabbani, whose Jamiat-e-Islami rebel group largely controls the
strategic Salang Highway leading from the Afghan capital to the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
