<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-US-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0722 12-11 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-US-Armenia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0722,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian-Americans Do What They Can For Quake Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with telethon drawing
$2.8 million in pledges, service in Boston. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Once again...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenian-Americans attended church services Sunday
to pray for those killed in the earthquake that shattered their
homeland, consoling each other with tales of the endurance of their
people and marveling at others' generosity.
   ``It's something that is going to be in Armenian memories
forever,'' Odette Hambarsoomian, 28, said of the quake while waiting
for Mass to begin at St. Mary's Armenian Apostolic Church in the Los
Angeles suburb of Glendale.
   ``There's not any family here that does not have relatives in
Armenia,'' said the Rev. Nareg Shrikian in Glendale.
   A hastily assembled telethon drew $2.8 million in pledges, said
Los Angeles station KSCI-TV. The telethon, which ran from midnight
Saturday to 6 a.m. Sunday on the West Coast, was shown on that
station, on cable channels throughout Southern California, and on
independent stations in Houston; Norfolk, Va.; Seattle; San
Francisco; and Sacramento, Calif.
   In Cambridge, Mass., Cardinal Bernard Law participated in a Mass
with about 200 Armenians on Sunday and announced that a special
collection made Sunday at churches in the Boston Roman Catholic
Archdiocese would go toward relief efforts.
   ``Once again, the Armenian people around the world are undergoing
another tragedy,'' said Bishop Norvan Zakarian of Lyon, France,
delivering a guest sermon during Mass at Saint Vartan Cathedral in
New York City, the diocesan headquarters for the Armenian Church of
America. ``The whole Armenian people of the world are in deep
mourning.''
   Zakarian's remarks in Armenian were translated for reporters by
an Armenian-American journalist.
   ``We Armenians are used to destruction and desolation,'' the Rev.
Garen Gdanian said at St. Peter's Armenian Apostolic Church in
Watervliet, N.Y., near Albany.
   Gdanian touched on the various empires that have subjugated the
Armenian people through the centuries, from the Mongols to the Turks.
   ``But little Armenia is still sticking around. Where are all
those others?'' he asked.
   In Syracuse, N.Y., tiny St. John's Armenian Apostolic Church is
too small to have a permanent priest so it had no special service
Sunday. But church member Garbis Garboushian said his 40-member
congregation had managed to raise a few thousand dollars and collect
clothing, blankets and boots for the quake victims.
   ``The church hall is quite full,'' he said.
   St. Paul's Armenian Apostolic Church, also in Syracuse, had
received between $3,000 and $5,000 in donations, mostly from
non-Armenian churches, said parish council chairman Mike Mikaelian.
   ``The generosity of the public is fantastic,'' said Edward
Belemjian, parish council chairman for St. Peter's in Watervliet.
``At work people come up to me and give me checks without my
asking.''
   ``Little children have come in and given us their Christmas
donations,'' said Hazel Barsamian, who is working with the Armenian
Relief Society's Chicago chapter.
   ``This little girl came with her grandfather and she apparently
had a piggy bank that she was saving for Christmas. She said
`Grandpa, instead of me getting something, why don't I give this'''
for the earthquake victims, Ms. Barsamian said.
   In New York City, the Rev. Yeznig Balian and others noted that
the very fact that the Soviet Union agreed to accept help from the
outside, including the United States, was one encouraging outgrowth
of the tragedy.
   ``If there is any silver lining to a tragedy like this, it would
be the openness of the system right now,'' Balian said.
   While many kept busy gathering donations of money and supplies,
others had more personal concerns.
   For Gerry Nazarian in New York, the quest for information was
sadly fruitful. He spoke to relatives in California, who called
family in Moscow, who reached relatives in Yerevan, who got hold of
family members in Leninakan, one of the hardest-hit cities.
   ``The last word we had last night (was that) two of our cousins
are dead,'' Nazarian said. ``They were in an office and the entire
office building collapsed. ... It's terrible, terrible. I couldn't
sleep all night. I mean, the whole family is so upset.
   ``It's ... that pain _ you just can't describe it.''
   ``Armenians have a way of surviving. We have a history of this
kind of tragedy,'' said Ms. Barsamian in Chicago. ``We are fighters,
we are survivors, we stand together and we will survive. And we will
help.''
</TEXT>
