<HEAD>Atlantis Begins Return Trip to Florida With California-To-Arizona
Hop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Atlantis landing in Arizona. No pickup.
^Precede EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Space Shuttle Atlantis, riding
piggy-back atop a modified Boeing 747, completed the first leg of
its return trip to Florida on Sunday, officials said.
   The orbiter, back from a classified military space flight,
arrived at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base here at 5:55 p.m., after a
90-minute flight from Edwards Air Force Base in California,
officials said.
   The crew of the piggy-back flight planned to wait overnight for
weather reports, said Joseph D'Agostino, spokesman for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration. Rain in Texas and Florida on
Sunday, if it continued, could delay completion of the flight to
Cape Canaveral on Monday, he said.
   Flying through rain can damage the thousands of ceramic tiles
affixed to the shuttle's belly to ward off the heat of re-entry into
the Earth's atmosphere, D'Agostino said.
   The return trip probably would be completed in two more hops,
D'Agostino said: from Davis-Monthan to Kelly Air Force Base outside
San Antonio, Texas, and then to Florida.
</TEXT>
