<DATELINE>CARTHAGE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A natural gas pipeline exploded and burned
Sunday, forcing residents of two nearby subdivisions to be evacuated
for about three hours before the fire was controlled, authorities
said.
   The explosion occurred just after 3:30 p.m. about five miles west
of Carthage, a town of 6,500 in Panola County near the Louisiana
border, said Travis Cadenhead, dispatcher for the Carthage Fire
Department.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   ``It's a pretty good explosion,'' he said. ``I don't know what
the damage is.''
   Two small subdivisions, with about 30 homes and 100 residents,
were evacuated as a precaution for about three hours, authorities
said.
   Firefighters shut off the flow of gas and then brought the flames
under control. U.S. Highway 79, closed while the fire was being
controlled, was reopened about 6:15 p.m.
   Mary Minigh, a dispatcher for the Carthage Police Department,
said her granddaughter, who lives across from the gas line, told her
she saw a cloud of black smoke cover the highway and heard an
explosion.
