<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     12-11 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likud And Labor Resume Coalition Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, leader of the
right-wing Likud bloc, renewed talks Sunday with the rival Labor
Party in hopes of forming a national unity government by week's end,
Israel radio said.
   Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, leader of left-leaning
Labor, agreed each party would set up a three-member negotiating
team to hammer out the coalition agreement, the radio said.
   In elections last month, Likud won 40 seats and Labor won 39. But
Likud was able to forge a tentative coalition with small Orthodox
and extreme right-wing parties, giving it control over more than
half of the 120-member Parliament and the upper hand in coalition
talks.
   ``We should not stretch out these negotiations,'' said Moshe
Shahal, a member of Labor's negotiating team. ``It should take two
or three days.''
   A Likud spokesman told the radio the new government would be
similar to the joint government formed after the 1984 elections
ended in a stalemate. Peres was prime minister for two years and
handed power to Shamir in 1986.
   But it is unlikely that Likud will agree this time to share the
prime ministry with Labor.
   For the last four years, the policy of the coalition government
has been paralyzed by disagreements on the future of the occupied
territories and peace negotiations.
   Likud and Labor still are split over the proposal to hold an
international Middle East conference, which Peres favors; and over
the establishment of new Jewish settlements in the occupied areas.
Likud and its allies want new settlements.
   Likud has offered Labor the Foreign Ministry on condition that
Labor pursue no new diplomatic initiatives without Likud's approval.
The demand was seen as a way of stifling Peres' call for the
international peace conference.
</TEXT>
