<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BuriedBodies     12-11 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buried Bodies,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Link Landlady To Eighth Body</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Sunday they believe a man
whose body was left in a wooden box on a riverbank three years ago
was a tenant of the woman who ran a boardinghouse where seven bodies
have been unearthed.
   Authorities said the latest body linked to Dorothea Montalvo
Puente was dumped on the Sacramento River's east bank in adjacent
Sutter County more than two years before the bodies were buried in
the yard of Puente's downtown boardinghouse. Those seven bodies were
discovered last month.
   Puente, 59, has been charged with one count of murder in the
boardinghouse case, and additional counts are expected to be filed
in January. Coroner's officials have said the boardinghouse victims
all died in 1988. Police believe they were tenants killed by Puente
for their Social Security checks.
   On Saturday, police arrested Ismael Carrasco Florez, 46, a
Sacramento handyman authorities accused of building the coffinlike
box for Puente and helping her truck it to the river in late 1985.
   Florez was booked in Sacramento County jail on suspicion of being
an accessory to murder. He was released later the same day on $3,000
bail.
   ``Florez has been identified as the subject who built the wooden
box in which a victim was placed and then transported to Sutter
County by he and Dorothea Puente,'' police Capt. Michael O'Kane said.
   The name of the victim was withheld until his identity could be
confirmed. He was described as a 55-year-old white man with a
mustache and false teeth. O'Kane said earlier reports that the
victim was a woman were incorrect.
   Asked if police believe Puente might be linked to any deaths
beyond the eight, O'Kane said: ``That's a possibility, but we have
to deal with how many people we can trace to her and where they
are.''
   He said investigators are still trying to locate two former
tenants of the boardinghouse, which catered largely to poor people
and alcoholics. ``There may be a couple we may never find,'' he
said. ``That doesn't mean they have been are slain. It could mean
they just disappeared.''
   The body found in Sutter County was discovered by a fisherman on
New Year's Day 1986, about two miles south of Verona and about 20
miles north of Sacramento. O'Kane said the man had been dead two to
four weeks when his body was discovered in well-made, 6-foot plywood
coffin.
   O'Kane said Sutter County authorities contacted police about a
possible link between the body and Puente because it had been
wrapped in plastic like many of the bodies unearthed in the yard of
her rooming house.
   Police traced Florez through the registration of a pickup truck
he once owned. O'Kane said Florez did a variety of carpentry jobs
for Puente at the boardinghouse but hasn't been linked to any of the
other deaths.
   The handyman told police that he didn't know what was in the box,
The Sacramento Bee reported Sunday. Police spoke to him at his home
Friday and took him Saturday to the river bank where the body was
found.
</TEXT>
