<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0660 12-11 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tutu Challenges Government To Try Him For Treason</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Botha-Mandela, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 7th ```Whatever happens...' to ADD
names of front's senior leaders, PICKS UP 8th pvs `The fourth...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu on
Sunday challenged the government to charge him with treason, saying
he is as guilty as four black activists sentenced to prison last
week.
   Also Sunday, a human rights group released the text of an open
letter to President P.W. Botha from blacks detained without charge
at Johannesburg Prison, demanding that they be tried or freed.
   In an article in the Sunday Star newspaper, Tutu protested the
sentences imposed Thursday at the end of a three-year treason trial.
Four activists, including three senior leaders of the United
Democratic Front, received prison terms ranging from six to 12 years
for treason.
   Tutu, leader of the Anglican Church in southern Africa, was a
sponsor of the United Democratic Front when the nationwide
anti-apartheid coalition was formed in 1983 and has supported it
steadfastly since then.
   The group was banned in February, and the judge in the treason
trial declared it a revolutionary organization which sought the
violent overthrow of the government.
   ``If these four men have committed treason, then I have committed
treason and should face charges as well,'' Tutu wrote. He urged that
the four be granted bail during an appeal process.
   ``Whatever happens, I will campaign as I have never campaigned
before until they are released,'' he said. ``Whether or not the law
was properly applied, the effect of this judgment will be to
discourage people from peaceful opposition.''
   Convicted were Patrick Lekota, a spokesman for the front; its
national secretary Popo Molefe; and Moses Chikane, the Transvaal
Province branch secretary.
   The fourth activist convicted of treason, along with front
leaders, was Tom Manthata, a South African Council of Churches field
worker. Manthata was dispatched by Tutu in 1984 to monitor the
township rioting which prompted the treason charges.
   The Johannesburg detainees, in a letter released by South
Africa's recently established Human Rights Commission, said they
would observe a one-day fast Monday to protest the 30-month-old
state of emergency.
   Emergency regulations allow indefinite detention without charge.
An estimated 30,000 people have been detained for varying periods
during the emergency, and about 1,000 are believed held at present.
   In their letter to Botha, the detainees said: ``We have in our
midst people who have been kept more than 24 months in detention...
We have children whose lives are being wasted here and who may not
recuperate from the effects of detention... Some held with us have
been tortured.''
   ``If you are convinced that we committed some sort of crime, you
have the courts of law to try us,'' the letter said. ``It is against
this background that we categorically demand our immediate release.''
   The Human Rights Commission, in an accompanying statement, said
there were about 180 detainees at Johannesburg Prison. It described
them as ``prisoners of war in a country that is in a state of civil
war with its own citizens.''
   In a separate development, the main association of Afrikaner
business executives said a fact-finding team sent to Western Europe
had concluded that tougher sanctions against South Africa were
inevitable unless major political changes took place.
   The team said Europe's attitude would soften only if South Africa
adopted a political system acceptable to a majority of blacks, who
at present have no vote in national affairs. Gradual reforms such as
those advocated by the government would not be sufficient to avert
tougher embargos, the group said.
   South Africa's mainly Dutch-descended Afrikaners make up about 60
percent of the white population of 5 million and dominate the
governing National Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
