<DOCNO> AP881211-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 2145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeaParty     12-11 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tea Party,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Watch Re-enactment of Boston Tea Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people turned out Sunday night to
remember one of America's most celebrated protests as the 215th
anniversary of the Boston Tea Party approaches.
   But it was the leaves of trees, not tea, that members of area
militia groups dumped overboard from the Brig Beaver II, a replica
of the original vessel, into Boston Harbor.
   The militia men dressed as Indians to re-enact the Dec. 16, 1773,
dumping that revolutionaries carried out to protect tariffs on one
of their favorite brews.
   The celebration was held Sunday, a few days before the
anniversary, to attract more spectators. The Boston Tea Party Ship
and Museum offered free admission all day.
   ``The commemorative re-enactment is part of the Boston Tea Party
Ship and Museum's ongoing effort to remind Americans that our right
to non-violent protest started here,'' the museum said in an
announcement.
</TEXT>
