<DOCNO> AP881211-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 2202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     12-11 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Heidi Chronicles,' A New Play by Wendy Wasserstein, Opens
Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heidi Holland knows about art and artists,
especially little-known female painters of the last several hundred
years. She can talk at length about their work and how they were
ignored or denigrated by other painters, the public or both. In
these respects, she's a knowledgable woman.
   What Heidi doesn't know about is life, particularly the problem
of sorting out what kind of person she would like to be if she ever
becomes an adult. That's a lot harder to deal with, she says.
   But the woman makes an attempt to find out about herself in ``The
Heidi Chronicles,'' Wendy Wasserstein's perceptive and very funny
new play about what it's like growing up female in the 1960s, '70s
and '80s.
   The play, which opened Sunday at off-Broadway's Playwrights
Horizons, traces one woman's confusion, from the tentative
beginnings of the woman's movement in the 1960s to the post-feminism
of today when ``traditional values,'' that favorite buzz word of
current politicians, have reasserted themselves with a vengeance.
   In between, Heidi takes a Candide-like journey that carries her
through various stages of social, sexual and political awareness.
She travels pretty much as an outsider, looking in on the problems
and foibles of her friends and lovers. But unlike Candide, she
questions everything and everybody she comes across.
   The people she meets _ and they keep popping up with some
regularity _ include Scoop Rosenbaum, a cocky journalist who starts
out working for something called the Liberation Earth News in the
late 1960s and ends up as the owner of Boomer, a big magazine
success of 20 years later. The two start out as lovers and end up as
friends.
   Her other constant male friend is a caustic young man who becomes
the most successful pediatrician in Manhattan. He also happens to be
gay, a fact he reveals to Heidi during a demonstration at the Art
Institute of Chicago against its sexist exhibition policies.
   Heidi also watches the evolution of her best friend Susan who
goes from clerking for a Supreme Court justice to tending sheep on a
woman's collective in Montana to producing a successful television
series. That certainly is some resume, but not an unlikely
combination for Miss Wasserstein to concoct. The playwright, who
also wrote the equally hilarious ``Isn't It Romantic,'' is a witty
social commentator with a deadly accuracy for skewering the trendy
conventions of our time.
   Despite its many laughs, the play has serious intentions, too.
The evening culminates dramatically in an impassionated speech by
Heidi to her high school alumnae society. In it, the woman explains
that she is still unhappy despite some success in life.
   ``I thought the whole point was that we wouldn't feel stranded,''
Heidi proclaims. ``I thought the point was we were all in this
together.''
   The play ends on a surprising note, perhaps too surprising for
what has gone before, but it's a hopeful note, too, suggesting that
Miss Wasserstein has not lost her belief that things really have
gotten better for women.
   Joan Allen portrays Heidi as an intellectual idealist, trying to
rationalize her way into doing the right thing. Her indecision is
fascinating to watch. It's an incisive performance.
   Peter Friedman is oily but charming as the aggressive Scoop. He
keeps the man's obnoxiousness at bay, as he climbs the ladder of
yuppie success. Boyd Gaines' gay doctor masks a compassion behind an
acid-tongued exterior, and his conflict adds an undertone of
darkness to what could be just a comic part. Among the other members
of the large cast, Joanne Camp makes a strong impression in several
roles, particularly a strident feminist and a tough but shallow
television talk show host.
   Director Daniel Sullivan has marshaled the play's many scenes as
if they were revue sketches. The pace is as fast as the quick
movement of Thomas Lynch's mobile settings that glide and fly across
the tiny stage. The costumes by Jennifer von Mayrhauser accurately
mirror the nearly 25-year span the play covers.
   ``The Heidi Chronicles'' is a modern-day, feminist Odyssey told
with wit, style and a great deal of compassion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
