<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TownNoLonger     12-11 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Town No Longer,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Of Lynhurst No Longer Exists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNHURST, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When residents of this town on the west
side of Indianapolis woke up Sunday, their 56 houses were still
standing but their town no longer existed.
   A resolution signed by Indianapolis Mayor William H. Hudnut two
months ago took effect Saturday and dissolved the financially
troubled Marion County town.
   Lynhurst was once on the outskirts of Indianapolis. In the
mid-1970s, however, the city government and city boundaries were
reorganized to cover the whole of Marion County. But town boards
with limited powers still existed in many of the villages in the
county.
   In Lynhurst, town board members voted 2-1 in late July to being
dissolution procedures, because they could find no way to pay a
$4,100 bill owed to the Wayne Township Fire Department.
   Town Board President Mary Jane Kern said the town also had other
outstanding bills totaling less than $500. The town had $36,000 in
other funds, mostly from the state highway department, but that
money could not legally be used to pay the outstanding debts.
   The remaining funds, and the responsibility for paying the
outstanding bills, now go to the city-county government.
</TEXT>
