<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Spy,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Warrant Issued For Spy Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Berlin justice officials said they issued an
arrest warrant Sunday for a 47-year-old businessman suspected of
being involved in a spy ring that delivered military secrets to the
Soviets.
   ``Three people are being investigated on suspicion of
espionage,'' said Detlev Achammer, a spokesman for the West Berlin
Justice Department. He refused to identify the suspects or provide
details.
   An arrest warrant for a second suspect was issued on Thursday,
Achammer said.
   A spokesman for the federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe said
Friday that a man was detained and questioned in Munich in
connection with the investigation.
   Spokesman Hans-Juergen Foerster said the man was released because
of lack of evidence.
   Neither spokesman would comment on newspaper reports that the
trio obtained secret documents detailing the sophisticated
electronic systems of West Germany's Leopard II tank.
   The Cologne Express newspaper on Saturday reported that some of
the documents were delivered to the KGB, the Soviet intelligence
agency.
   It said the suspected agents worked with a KGB contact officer
stationed with the Soviet trade mission in East Berlin.
   In a related report, the Welt am Sonntag newspaper said Sunday
that a woman suspect told authorities that she and her husband
worked for the KGB for years.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified security sources in Bonn,
said the suspects delivered secret documents to the Soviets
detailing the tank's electronic target guidance system and its
onboard computer.
