<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1523EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-KodakPollution Bjt   12-11 1095</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak Pollution, Bjt,1132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Is it Pollution or Just a Public Relations Problem for Kodak?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The environmental mess that has plagued
Eastman Kodak Co. for nearly a year may be more a result of emotions
and coincidences, than pollution and poisons.
   No one can say for sure.
   But the company, once considered the benevolent corporate father
who could do no wrong, has certainly suffered a major blow to its
status in its hometown.
   ``Clearly, our reputation, at least as an environmentally
responsible company, has been brought into question. And we don't
like that,'' said Ron Roberts, a company spokesman.
   The whole mess started last March when a newspaper article
disclosed that some testing by Kodak indicated that chemicals had
probably leaked from Kodak Park, the company's sprawling
manufacturing complex, into the groundwater of a neighboring
residential area.
   Wall Street analysts and others took notice, but quickly lost
interest.
   ``I think the view down here was, `Is this going to be
catastrophic? Are we talking billions or hundreds of millions of
dollars?''' said Eugene Glazer, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. ``We looked at it and the answer was no.''
   That left the issue to be hashed out in the community.
   Since the first report, rhetoric and charges have been furiously
flying in numerous public hearings and blanket media coverage. A
$200 million lawsuit has been filed against the company. A major
expansion project to produce more color film has been stalled.
   Residents of Rand Street have appeared on television news
broadcasts to detail their dizziness, headaches and unexplained nose
bleeds. They've also held news conferences and protests.
   One woman even put her pet rabbit, who died during the uproar, in
the freezer to save as possible proof that chemicals were moving out
of the ground and into her home.
   ``The way this thing was presented it sounded like Kodak was
poisoning the neighborhood,'' said Dr. Joel Nitzkin, director of the
Monore County Health Department. ``It's all been taken out of
context. There just isn't any evidence of any health hazard.''
   His department conducted studies immediately after the newspaper
report and found nothing unusual in the Rand Street neighborhood.
Many of the complaints were exaggerated or had common explanations,
like having a home that was too dry in the winter.
   Months later, the health department conducted more tests in two
schools near the manufacturing center and pronounced them safe.
   ``Yes, we found contamination, from the cleaning agents used in
the schools, nothing from Kodak,'' said Nitzkin.
   Despite these preliminary findings, the mess at Kodak has become
messier and messier.
   After months of delays, more definitive testing, which will
involve taking soil samples from several feet underground in
backyards in the neighborhood, was started this past week.
   ``We're still on the road to finding out what's going on. It's
been a long and frustrating road so far,'' said Allen Hall,
co-chairman of Concerned Neighbors of Kodak Park, a neighborhood
group formed last March.
   Hall moved out of the neighborhood three weeks ago ``because I
didn't feel safe there any more.''
   His new neighborhood, in the Rochester suburb of Greece, is
quiet, odor-free and ``there's no fly ash on the window sill.''
   The Hall family is one of about 50 who have taken advantage of a
Kodak plan that helps people sell their homes or, if they want to
stay, refinances their mortgage at an attractive rate and gives them
up to $5,000 for home improvements.
   There are about 200 homes in the neighborhood.
   Meanwhile, two other former residents of the neighborhood hired
some expert environmental attorneys and filed a lawsuit claiming
``residents of the area are in grave danger.'' They hope to persuade
state Supreme Court Justice Raymond Cornelius to grant the suit
class action status.
   On the heels of the Rand Street situation, a new federal law
required Kodak and every other company in the country that uses
chemicals to disclose how many and how much of them were being
discharged into the environment.
   When the company in July revealed that 9 million pounds of
methylene chloride were being released into the air, albeit in very
diffuse amounts, people were shocked.
   ``Any time you talk about millions of pounds of anything, it
blows peoples' minds,'' said Robert Wilson, an assistant professor
of environmental health sciences at the University of Rochester.
   But, he said, that number is nearly as frightening as it sounds
because studies on the dangers of methylene chloride are ``very
equivocal.''
   Methylene chloride, a powerful solvent that's used in paint
strippers, spray paint, and as an industrial solvent, is at the
center of this environmental controversy.
   Kodak, the largest user of the solvent in New York, uses it
around the clock as a key ingredient in the manufacture of miles and
miles of photographic film.
   Within the last 10 years, the safety of exposure to the chemical
has come under scrutiny and in 1985 the chemical was listed as a B-2
probable carcinogen by the Environmental Protection Agency.
   That means that there's sufficient evidence from research in
animals to indicate that a chemical could cause cancer, but no
evidence in humans.
   In fact, the EPA used a comprehensive Kodak study of its own
workers exposed to the chemical to determine that there were no
significant increases in the incidence of cancer.
   In October, the company gathered a panel of 16 experts to review
the current information on methylene chloride and offer an opinion
on the danger of exposure to the chemical.
   ``The bottom line is that when the panel members were asked if
they would be content to live in an atmosphere that contained what
Rochester's contained, the answer was `absolutely,''' said Dr.
Marvin Kuschner, chairman of the panel and a professor of pathology
at the State University of New York at Stony Brook.
   The final piece of the pollution puzzle occurred last month when,
with concerns of pollution at their height, Kodak requested a permit
to release additional methylene chloride into the air because of its
planned expansion.
   The company is challenging the state's recently revised limits on
emissions and the state has promised a ruling later this month.
   ``I don't know why all these things have happened at the same
time. I don't have the luxury to think about that,'' said Al Butkas,
chief supervisor of Kodak affairs for the state Department of
Environmental Conservation. ``It would have been a lot nicer if each
one of these things had come in separate five-year blocks, I can
tell you that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
