<HEAD>Mexican Workers Won't Recover Lost Ground, Businessman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers should maintain the buying power they
have left next year but will not recover lost ground with raises in
January, a business leader said.
   The Minimum Wage Commission begins negotiations Thursday on the
amount of the annual Jan. 1 increase.
   Both inflation and the exchange rate must be considered in
figuring the amount of the raise, Jorge Ocejo Moreno, president of
the Mexican Employers' Federation, said Saturday.
   The minimum wage has been about $3.50 a day in Mexico City since
March.
   A government anti-inflation program begun a year ago held the
increase in consumer prices to 48.6 percent for the first 11 months
of this year. The plan was announced as inflation rose to 159.2
percent for all of 1987.
   As part of the program, the peso currency, which had been
devalued daily, has been held steady.
</TEXT>
