<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Citicorp-Caribank     12-11 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citicorp-Caribank,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citicorp Buys Insolvent Caribank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caribank's 14 branches in South Florida will
be open for business as usual under the Citicorp name Monday morning.
   Citibank, the nation's largest bank holding company, bought the
bank Friday along with the responsibility for $15 million in red ink
stemming from bad real estate loans, state regulators said.
   Under the agreement, Citibank will purchase around $535 million
in Caribank assets and will assume $500 million in deposits. In
addition, Citicorp will inject about $50 million in capital into the
new entity, to be called Citibank (Florida) NA, which will maintain
headquarters in Dania.
   Caribank has been under close regulatory supervision since early
1986 and was ruled insolvent this year by the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. and the state of Florida, Comptroller Gerald Lewis
said.
   ``This is a happy ending to a bad situation,'' Lewis said.
``We're pleased that Citicorp was interested in this institution,
and we hope that its future will be brighter than its past.''
   Caribank had about $507 million in assets but had suffered losses
of about $45.3 million in 1988 as of Nov. 30, said Lisa McKnight, a
spokeswoman for Lewis.
   ``The capital just wasn't there, so they became insovlent. The
severity of the problem had increased drastically,'' Ms. McKnight
said.
   Citicorp had assets of approximately $205 billion and 34 thrifts
in Florida as of June 3O.
</TEXT>
