<DOCNO> AP881211-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-88 1847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SuperBowl-Hotels     12-11 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Bowl-Hotels,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Seeking Hotel Rooms For Super Bowl Are Told `No Room In La
Casa'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 26,000 hotel rooms in Dade and Broward
counties are already booked for the Super Bowl and people who
haven't taken steps to find lodging may soon be out of luck.
   Many fans are on waiting lists, and many of the top hotels are
asking a minimum four-day stay.
   ``No room in la casa,'' said Lisa Cole, spokeswoman for the
1,200-room Fontainebleau Hilton. ``We've been booked a solid year.''
   The story was the same at the Biscayne Bay Marriott. It has been
booked for three months, with 100 people on a waiting list, and it's
still getting 20 calls a day. The sister Marriott at Miami
International Airport is booked. So is the Marriott Harbor Beach
Resort in Fort Lauderdale.
   Other hotels that are booked include the Hyatt Regency, the Eden
Roc, the Intercontinental, the Shelborne and just about every other
major Miami area hotel, as well as the Diplomat in Hollywood, Pier
66 in Fort Lauderdale, and the Embassy Suites in Broward County,
just to name a few.
   The National Football League alone has reserved more than 10,000
rooms for teams and their families, sponsors and the media. Fans
have taken about 16,000 more.
   Analysts estimate the need by game day Jan. 22 at about 35,000
rooms.
   ``This isn't the type that drives up and down the strip looking
for a vacancy,'' said Jim Steeg, NFL director of special events and
1-year veteran Super Bowl organizer.
   One reason for the early booking may have been previous Super
Bowl experiences.
   At the last Miami Super Bowl in 1979, when the Steelers slid by
the Cowboys, 35-31, travel agents had booked many hotels solid,
leaving NFL teams and affiliates fumbling for rooms.
   ``That was sort of upsetting,'' Steeg said.
   There is hope for those still looking for rooms, however.
   Ron Kent, executive director of the Super Bowl Host Committee,
said between 6,000 and 7,000 rooms are still available in Dade and
another 4,000 to 5,000 are available in Broward.
   Kent said even more rooms will become available as fans see their
teams shot as the playoffs dwindle and opt to cancel reservations.
   And some people have gone as far as Fort Myers, across the
Florida peninsula, to secure their Super Bowl rooms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
