<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury 1stLd-Writethru f0022 12-11 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0022,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with details, background; No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Raises Offer for Pillsbury; Company Chairmen Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food giant Pillsbury Co. announced late Sunday
that suitor Grand Metropolitan PLC of Britain is willing to raise
its offer for Pillsbury to as much as $66 a share from the current
$60 bid.
   A $66-a-share bid would raise the offer for Pillsbury to $5.6
billion. Grand Met had been trying to take over Pillsbury for $5.23
billion. Pillsbury has around 85.4 million shares outstanding.
   Pillsbury said in a statement that its chairman, Philip L. Smith,
had met over the weekend with Grand Met Chief Executive Officer
Allen Sheppard. The meetings did not result in any agreement between
Pillsbury and Grand Met, a major hotel and beverage conglomerate,
Pillsbury noted.
   The announcement came a day before the takeover battle is to come
to a head Monday, when a Delaware court holds hearings on
Pillsbury's anti-takeover poison pill, the cornerstone of its
defense against Grand Met.
   Last month, Minneapolis-based Pillsbury announced it would make
its Burger King Corp. a separate company, complete with its own
board of directors and newly issued stock. The spinoff would occur
Dec. 19.
   The move has been widely viewed as a last-ditch effort by
Pillsbury to fend off Grand Met.
   Then, on Dec. 2, Pillsbury announced it has agreed to sell its
Grain Merchandising Division, a chain of restaurants and a food
division.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg denied that the sales, terms of
which were not disclosed, were made in reaction to the takeover
attempt. He added that plans to sell the Grain Merchandising
Division were announced July 25.
   Pillsbury sold the grain division to ConAgra Inc., a diversified
food company based in Omaha, Neb., with annual sales of $9.5
billion. Haeg said it was not known how much the division was worth,
but said it was part of the company's industrial foods division,
which had sales of $416 million last year.
   Pillsbury also said it was selling Bay Street, a chain of 12
seafood restaurants based in Dallas. The chain was sold to Bay
Street Restaurant Inc., a management group led by Bay Street General
Manager Alan R. Palmieri and Bill Bouffard, president of Restaurant
Capital Corp., an investment group.
   Also sold was Ashford Creameries, a division of Fiesta Foods Ltd.
of Britain, a marketer of frozen desserts and ice cream. It was sold
to London-based Hillsdown Holdings PLC.
   At an initial meeting on Friday evening, Pillsbury said, Sheppard
indicated he was prepared to increase Grand Met's offer to $63 a
share. Smith responded that he ``was not willing to discuss at this
time'' a price which was not in the range of $68 to $73 a share.
   On Saturday morning, Grand Met indicated it was making a formal
offer of $65 a share.
   Pillsbury said its board of directors met Sunday to consider the
$65-a-share proposal, but there was ``no enthusiasm'' for it.
   At a meeting on Sunday afternoon, Sheppard indicated that
although $65 was his official final offer, $66 a share ``could be
available,'' according to the statement.
   Pillsbury said its board has authorized Smith to be available for
any discussions with Grand Met officials ``which are designed to
maximize values to Pillsbury shareholders.''
   Attorneys for Grand Met have said the company would have to lower
its offer should the Burger King spinoff occur because it would
present a huge tax liability for Grand Met.
   Monday's hearing in Delaware Chancery Court is on Grand Met's
renewed motion directing Pillsbury to invalidate its ``poison pill''
defense. The pill would make a takeover prohibitively expensive. The
tender offer is conditioned on the removal of the pill.
   Dissident shareholders also have sued to have the pill
invalidated, but courts in Delaware and Minnesota have left it
intact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
